# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: field-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In mathematics, an **algebraic number field** (or simply **number field**) is an extension field K of the field of rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ such that the field extension $K/\mathbb {Q}$ has finite degree (and hence is an algebraic field extension).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Thus K is a field that contains $\mathbb {Q}$ and has finite dimension when considered as a vector space over $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The study of algebraic number fields, that is, of algebraic extensions of the field of rational numbers, is the central topic of algebraic number theory.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This study reveals hidden structures behind the rational numbers, by using algebraic methods.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The notion of algebraic number field relies on the concept of a field.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A field consists of a set of elements together with two operations, namely addition, and multiplication, and some distributivity assumptions.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] These operations make the field into an abelian group under addition, and they make the nonzero elements of the field into another abelian group under multiplication.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A prominent example of a field is the field of rational numbers, commonly denoted $\mathbb {Q}$ , together with its usual operations of addition and multiplication.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Another notion needed to define algebraic number fields is vector spaces.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] whose entries are elements of a fixed field, such as the field $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Any two such sequences can be added by adding the corresponding entries.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Furthermore, all members of any sequence can be multiplied by a single element *c* of the fixed field.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] These two operations known as vector addition and scalar multiplication satisfy a number of properties that serve to define vector spaces abstractly.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Vector spaces are allowed to be "infinite-dimensional", that is to say that the sequences constituting the vector spaces may be of infinite length.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] the vector space is said to be of finite dimension, n .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] An **algebraic number field** (or simply **number field**) is a finite-degree field extension of the field of rational numbers.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Here **degree** means the dimension of the field as a vector space over $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Every field extension **of finite degree** is algebraic.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Therefore, elements of K are also referred to as *algebraic numbers*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Given a polynomial p such that $p(f)=0$ , it can be arranged such that the leading coefficient $e_{m}$ is one, by dividing all coefficients by it, if necessary.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A polynomial with this property is known as a monic polynomial.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In general it will have rational coefficients.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] If, however, the monic polynomial's coefficients are actually all integers, f is called an *algebraic integer*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It can be shown that any algebraic integer that is also a rational number must actually be an integer, hence the name "algebraic integer".
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Again using abstract algebra, specifically the notion of a finitely generated module, it can be shown that the sum and the product of any two algebraic integers is still an algebraic integer.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It follows that the algebraic integers in K form a ring denoted ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ called the **ring of integers** of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It is a subring of (that is, a ring contained in) K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A field contains no zero divisors and this property is inherited by any subring, so the ring of integers of K is an integral domain.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The field K is the field of fractions of the integral domain ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This way one can get back and forth between the algebraic number field K and its ring of integers ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Rings of algebraic integers have three distinctive properties: firstly, ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ is an integral domain that is integrally closed in its field of fractions K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Secondly, ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ is a Noetherian ring.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Finally, every nonzero prime ideal of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ is maximal or, equivalently, the Krull dimension of this ring is one.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] An abstract commutative ring with these three properties is called a *Dedekind ring* (or *Dedekind domain*), in honor of Richard Dedekind, who undertook a deep study of rings of algebraic integers.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For general Dedekind rings, in particular rings of integers, there is a unique factorization of ideals into a product of prime ideals.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] However, unlike $\mathbf {Z}$ as the ring of integers of $\mathbf {Q}$ , the ring of integers of a proper extension of $\mathbf {Q}$ need not admit unique factorization of numbers into a product of prime numbers or, more precisely, prime elements.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Using the norm it can be shown that these two factorization are actually inequivalent in the sense that the factors do not just differ by a unit in ${\mathcal {O}}_{\mathbf {Q} ({\sqrt {-5}})}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Euclidean domains are unique factorization domains: For example $\mathbf {Z} [i]$ , the ring of Gaussian integers, and $\mathbf {Z} [\omega ]$ , the ring of Eisenstein integers, where $\omega$ is a cube root of unity (unequal to 1), have this property.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The failure of unique factorization is measured by the class number, commonly denoted *h*, the cardinality of the so-called ideal class group.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The ring of integers ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ possesses unique factorization if and only if it is a principal ring or, equivalently, if K has class number 1.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Given a number field, the class number is often difficult to compute.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The class number problem, going back to Gauss, is concerned with the existence of imaginary quadratic number fields (i.e., $\mathbf {Q} ({\sqrt {-d}}),d\geq 1$ ) with prescribed class number.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The class number formula relates *h* to other fundamental invariants of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] (The product is over all prime ideals of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ , $N({\mathfrak {p}})$ denotes the norm of the prime ideal or, equivalently, the (finite) number of elements in the residue field ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}/{\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The infinite product converges only for Re(*s*) > 1; in general analytic continuation and the functional equation for the zeta-function are needed to define the function for all *s*).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The Dedekind zeta-function generalizes the Riemann zeta-function in that ζ $\mathbb {Q}$ (*s*) = ζ(*s*).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Here *r*1 and *r*2 classically denote the number of real embeddings and pairs of complex embeddings of K , respectively.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Moreover, Reg is the regulator of K , *w* the number of roots of unity in K and *D* is the discriminant of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Dirichlet L-functions $L(\chi ,s)$ are a more refined variant of $\zeta (s)$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Both types of functions encode the arithmetic behavior of $\mathbb {Q}$ and K , respectively.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] with coprime a and m , there are infinitely many prime numbers.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This theorem is implied by the fact that the Dirichlet L -function is nonzero at $s=1$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Using much more advanced techniques including algebraic K-theory and Tamagawa measures, modern number theory deals with a description, if largely conjectural (see Tamagawa number conjecture), of values of more general L-functions.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] where now the *mi* are rational numbers.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The algebraic integers of K are then precisely those elements of K where the *mi* are all integers.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Working locally and using tools such as the Frobenius map, it is always possible to explicitly compute such a basis, and it is now standard for computer algebra systems to have built-in programs to do this.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] By the primitive element theorem, there exists such an x , called a primitive element.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] If x can be chosen in ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ and such that $B_{x}$ is a basis of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ as a free **Z**-module, then $B_{x}$ is called a power integral basis, and the field K is called a monogenic field.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] An example of a number field that is not monogenic was first given by Dedekind.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Recall that any field extension $K/\mathbb {Q}$ has a unique $\mathbb {Q}$ -vector space structure.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The rational numbers $a_{ij}$ are uniquely determined by x and the choice of a basis since any element of K can be uniquely represented as a linear combination of the basis elements.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This way of associating a matrix to any element of the field K is called the *regular representation*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The square matrix A represents the effect of multiplication by x in the given basis.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It follows that if the element y of K is represented by a matrix B , then the product $xy$ is represented by the matrix product $BA$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Invariants of matrices, such as the trace, determinant, and characteristic polynomial, depend solely on the field element x and not on the basis.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In particular, the trace of the matrix $A(x)$ is called the *trace* of the field element x and denoted ${\text{Tr}}(x)$ , and the determinant is called the *norm* of *x* and denoted $N(x)$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Now this can be generalized slightly by instead considering a field extension $K/L$ and giving an L -basis for K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Then, there is an associated matrix $A_{K/L}(x)$ , which has trace ${\text{Tr}}_{K/L}(x)$ and norm ${\text{N}}_{K/L}(x)$ defined as the trace and determinant of the matrix $A_{K/L}(x)$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] To this end, we take an arbitrary $y\in \mathbb {Q} (\theta )$ where $y=y_{0}+y_{1}\theta +y_{2}\theta ^{2}$ and compute the product $xy$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Here *λ* is a rational number, and *x*, *y* are any two elements of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The *trace form* derived is a bilinear form defined by means of the trace, as $Tr_{K/L}:K\otimes _{L}K\to L$ by $Tr_{K/L}(x\otimes y)=Tr_{K/L}(x\cdot y)$ and extending linearly.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The ***integral trace form***, an integer-valued symmetric matrix is defined as $t_{ij}={\text{Tr}}_{K/\mathbb {Q} }(b_{i}b_{j})$ , where *b*1, ..., *b*n is an integral basis for K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The *discriminant* of K is defined as det(*t*).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It is an integer, and is an invariant property of the field K , not depending on the choice of integral basis.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The matrix associated to an element *x* of K can also be used to give other, equivalent descriptions of algebraic integers.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] An element *x* of K is an algebraic integer if and only if the characteristic polynomial *p**A* of the matrix *A* associated to *x* is a monic polynomial with integer coefficients.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Suppose that the matrix *A* that represents an element *x* has integer entries in some basis *e*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] By the Cayley–Hamilton theorem, *p**A*(*A*) = 0, and it follows that *p**A*(*x*) = 0, so that *x* is an algebraic integer.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Conversely, if *x* is an element of K that is a root of a monic polynomial with integer coefficients then the same property holds for the corresponding matrix *A*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In this case it can be proven that *A* is an integer matrix in a suitable basis of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The property of being an algebraic integer is *defined* in a way that is independent of a choice of a basis in K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The "3" in the upper left hand corner of this matrix is the trace of the matrix of the map defined by the first basis element (1) in the regular representation of K on K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This basis element induces the identity map on the 3-dimensional vector space, K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The trace of the matrix of the identity map on a 3-dimensional vector space is 3.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The determinant of this is 1304 = 23·163, the field discriminant; in comparison the root discriminant, or discriminant of the polynomial, is 5216 = 25·163.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Mathematicians of the nineteenth century assumed that algebraic numbers were a type of complex number.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This situation changed with the discovery of p-adic numbers by Hensel in 1897; and now it is standard to consider all of the various possible embeddings of a number field K into its various topological completions $K_{\mathfrak {p}}$ at once.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A *place* of a number field K is an equivalence class of absolute values on K pg 9.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Essentially, an absolute value is a notion to measure the size of elements x of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Two such absolute values are considered equivalent if they give rise to the same notion of smallness (or proximity).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The equivalence relation between absolute values $|\cdot |_{0}\sim |\cdot |_{1}$ is given by some $\lambda \in \mathbb {R} _{>0}$ such that $|\cdot |_{0}=|\cdot |_{1}^{\lambda }$ meaning we take the value of the norm $|\cdot |_{1}$ to the $\lambda$ -th power.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In general, the types of places fall into three regimes.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Firstly (and mostly irrelevant), the trivial absolute value | |0, which takes the value 1 on all non-zero $x\in K$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The second and third classes are **Archimedean places** and **non-Archimedean (or ultrametric) places**.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The completion of K with respect to a place $|\cdot |_{\mathfrak {p}}$ is given in both cases by taking Cauchy sequences in K and dividing out null sequences, that is, sequences $\{x_{n}\}_{n\in \mathbb {N} }$ such that $|x_{n}|_{\mathfrak {p}}\to 0$ tends to zero when n tends to infinity.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This can be shown to be a field again, the so-called completion of K at the given place $|\cdot |_{\mathfrak {p}}$ , denoted $K_{\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For $K=\mathbb {Q}$ , the following non-trivial norms occur (Ostrowski's theorem): the (usual) absolute value, sometimes denoted $|\cdot |_{\infty }$ , which gives rise to the complete topological field of the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It is used to construct the p -adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In contrast to the usual absolute value, the *p*-adic absolute value gets *smaller* when *q* is multiplied by *p*, leading to quite different behavior of $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ as compared to $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Note the general situation typically considered is taking a number field K and considering a prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}\in {\text{Spec}}({\mathcal {O}}_{K})$ for its associated ring of algebraic numbers ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Then, there will be a unique place $|\cdot |_{\mathfrak {p}}:K\to \mathbb {R} _{\geq 0}$ called a non-Archimedean place.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In addition, for every embedding $\sigma :K\to \mathbb {C}$ there will be a place called an Archimedean place, denoted $|\cdot |_{\sigma }:K\to \mathbb {R} _{\geq 0}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This statement is a theorem also called Ostrowski's theorem.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The field $K=\mathbb {Q} [x]/(x^{6}-2)=\mathbb {Q} (\theta )$ for $\theta =\zeta {\sqrt[{6}]{2}}$ where $\zeta$ is a fixed 6th root of unity, provides a rich example for constructing explicit real and complex Archimedean embeddings, and non-Archimedean embeddings as wellpg 15-16.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Here we use the standard notation $r_{1}$ and $r_{2}$ for the number of real and complex embeddings used, respectively (see below).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Calculating the archimedean places of a number field K is done as follows: let x be a primitive element of K , with minimal polynomial f (over $\mathbb {Q}$ ).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Over $\mathbb {R}$ , f will generally no longer be irreducible, but its irreducible (real) factors are either of degree one or two.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Since there are no repeated roots, there are no repeated factors.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The roots r of factors of degree one are necessarily real, and replacing x by r gives an embedding of K into $\mathbb {R}$ ; the number of such embeddings is equal to the number of real roots of f .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Restricting the standard absolute value on $\mathbb {R}$ to K gives an archimedean absolute value on K ; such an absolute value is also referred to as a ***real place*** of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] On the other hand, the roots of factors of degree two are pairs of conjugate complex numbers, which allows for two conjugate embeddings into $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Either one of this pair of embeddings can be used to define an absolute value on K , which is the same for both embeddings since they are conjugate.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This absolute value is called a ***complex place*** of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] If all roots of f above are real (respectively, complex) or, equivalently, any possible embedding $K\subseteq \mathbb {C}$ is actually forced to be inside $\mathbb {R}$ (resp. not be inside $\mathbb {R}$ ), K is called totally real (resp. totally complex).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] To find the non-Archimedean places, let again f and x be as above.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ , f splits in factors of various degrees, none of which are repeated, and the degrees of which add up to n , the degree of f .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For each of these p -adically irreducible factors $f_{i}$ , we may suppose that x satisfies $f_{i}$ and obtain an embedding of K into an algebraic extension of finite degree over $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Such a local field behaves in many ways like a number field, and the p -adic numbers may similarly play the role of the rationals; in particular, we can define the norm and trace in exactly the same way, now giving functions mapping to $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For any ultrametric place *v* we have that |*x*|*v* ≤ 1 for any *x* in ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ , since the minimal polynomial for *x* has integer factors, and hence its *p*-adic factorization has factors in **Z***p*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Consequently, the norm term (constant term) for each factor is a *p*-adic integer, and one of these is the integer used for defining the absolute value for *v*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For an ultrametric place *v*, the subset of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ defined by |*x*|*v* < 1 is an ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Actually, ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is even a prime ideal.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Conversely, given a prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ , a discrete valuation can be defined by setting $v_{\mathfrak {p}}(x)=n$ where *n* is the biggest integer such that $x\in {\mathfrak {p}}^{n}$ , the *n*-fold power of the ideal.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This valuation can be turned into an ultrametric place.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Under this correspondence, (equivalence classes) of ultrametric places of K correspond to prime ideals of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For $K=\mathbb {Q}$ , this gives back Ostrowski's theorem: any prime ideal in **Z** (which is necessarily by a single prime number) corresponds to a non-Archimedean place and vice versa.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] However, for more general number fields, the situation becomes more involved, as will be explained below.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Yet another, equivalent way of describing ultrametric places is by means of localizations of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Given an ultrametric place v on a number field K , the corresponding localization is the subring T of K of all elements x such that | *x* |*v* ≤ 1.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] By the ultrametric property T is a ring.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Moreover, it contains ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For every element *x* of K , at least one of *x* or *x*−1 is contained in T .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Actually, since *K*×/*T*× can be shown to be isomorphic to the integers, T is a discrete valuation ring, in particular a local ring.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Actually, T is just the localization of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ at the prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}$ , so $T={\mathcal {O}}_{K,{\mathfrak {p}}}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Conversely, ${\mathfrak {p}}$ is the maximal ideal of T .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Altogether, there is a three-way equivalence between ultrametric absolute values, prime ideals, and localizations on a number field.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Some of the basic theorems in algebraic number theory are the going up and going down theorems, which describe the behavior of some prime ideal ${\mathfrak {p}}\in {\text{Spec}}({\mathcal {O}}_{K})$ when it is extended as an ideal in ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ for some field extension $L/K$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Since there exists a correspondence between places and prime ideals, this means we can find places dividing a place that is induced from a field extension.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] That is, if p is a place of K , then there are places v of L that divide p , in the sense that their induced prime ideals divide the induced prime ideal of p in ${\text{Spec}}({\mathcal {O}}_{L})$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In fact, this observation is usefulpg 13 while looking at the base change of an algebraic field extension of $\mathbb {Q}$ to one of its completions $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] If we write $K={\frac {\mathbb {Q} [X]}{Q(X)}}$ and write $\theta$ for the induced element of $X\in K$ , we get a decomposition of $K\otimes _{\mathbb {Q} }\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] has *n* points in each fiber over *t*, namely the *n* (complex) roots of *t*, except in t = *0*, where the fiber consists of only one element, *z* = 0.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] One says that the map is "ramified" in zero.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This is an example of a branched covering of Riemann surfaces.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This intuition also serves to define ramification in algebraic number theory.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Given a (necessarily finite) extension of number fields $K/L$ , a prime ideal *p* of ${\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ generates the ideal *pO**K* of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] with uniquely determined prime ideals *q**i* of ${\mathcal {O}}_{K}$ and numbers (called ramification indices) *e**i*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Whenever one ramification index is bigger than one, the prime *p* is said to ramify in K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The connection between this definition and the geometric situation is delivered by the map of spectra of rings $\mathrm {Spec} {\mathcal {O}}_{K}\to \mathrm {Spec} {\mathcal {O}}_{L}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In fact, unramified morphisms of schemes in algebraic geometry are a direct generalization of unramified extensions of number fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Ramification is a purely local property, i.e., depends only on the completions around the primes *p* and *q**i*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The inertia group measures the difference between the local Galois groups at some place and the Galois groups of the involved finite residue fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The following example illustrates the notions introduced above.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] at 23, it suffices to consider the field extension $\mathbb {Q} _{23}(x)/\mathbb {Q} _{23}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Substituting *x* = *y* + 10 in the first factor *g* modulo 529 yields *y* + 191, so the valuation | *y* |*g* for *y* given by *g* is | −191 |23 = 1.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] On the other hand, the same substitution in *h* yields *y*2 − 161*y* − 161 modulo 529.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Since possible values for the absolute value of the place defined by the factor *h* are not confined to integer powers of 23, but instead are integer powers of the square root of 23, the ramification index of the field extension at 23 is two.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The valuations of any element of K can be computed in this way using resultants.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] If, for example *y* = *x*2 − *x* − 1, using the resultant to eliminate *x* between this relationship and *f* = *x*3 − *x* − 1 = 0 gives *y*3 − 5*y*2 + 4*y* − 1 = 0.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Much of the significance of the discriminant lies in the fact that ramified ultrametric places are all places obtained from factorizations in $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ where *p* divides the discriminant.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This is even true of the polynomial discriminant; however the converse is also true, that if a prime *p* divides the discriminant, then there is a *p*-place that ramifies.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For this converse the field discriminant is needed.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This is the **Dedekind discriminant theorem**.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In the example above, the discriminant of the number field $\mathbb {Q} (x)$ with *x*3 − *x* − 1 = 0 is −23, and as we have seen the 23-adic place ramifies.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The Dedekind discriminant tells us it is the only ultrametric place that does.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The other ramified place comes from the absolute value on the complex embedding of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Generally in abstract algebra, field extensions *K* / *L* can be studied by examining the Galois group Gal(*K* / *L*), consisting of field automorphisms of K leaving L elementwise fixed.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] As an example, the Galois group $\mathrm {Gal} (\mathbb {Q} (\zeta _{n})/\mathbb {Q} )$ of the cyclotomic field extension of degree *n* (see above) is given by (**Z**/*n***Z**)×, the group of invertible elements in **Z**/*n***Z**.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This is the first stepstone into Iwasawa theory.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The fundamental theorem of Galois theory links fields in between K and its algebraic closure and closed subgroups of Gal(*K*).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For example, the abelianization (the biggest abelian quotient) *G*ab of *G* corresponds to a field referred to as the maximal abelian extension *K*ab (called so since any further extension is not abelian, i.e., does not have an abelian Galois group).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] By the Kronecker–Weber theorem, the maximal abelian extension of $\mathbb {Q}$ is the extension generated by all roots of unity.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For more general number fields, class field theory, specifically the Artin reciprocity law gives an answer by describing *G*ab in terms of the idele class group.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Also notable is the Hilbert class field, the maximal abelian unramified field extension of K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] It can be shown to be finite over K , its Galois group over K is isomorphic to the class group of K , in particular its degree equals the class number *h* of K (see above).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In certain situations, the Galois group acts on other mathematical objects, for example a group.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Such a group is then also referred to as a Galois module.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This enables the use of group cohomology for the Galois group Gal(*K*), also known as Galois cohomology, which in the first place measures the failure of exactness of taking Gal(*K*)-invariants, but offers deeper insights (and questions) as well.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For example, the Galois group *G* of a field extension *L* / *K* acts on *L*×, the nonzero elements of *L*.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This Galois module plays a significant role in many arithmetic dualities, such as Poitou-Tate duality.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The Brauer group of K , originally conceived to classify division algebras over K , can be recast as a cohomology group, namely H2(Gal (*K*, *K*×)).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Generally speaking, the term "local to global" refers to the idea that a global problem is first done at a local level, which tends to simplify the questions.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Then, of course, the information gained in the local analysis has to be put together to get back to some global statement.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For example, the notion of sheaves reifies that idea in topology and geometry.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Number fields share a great deal of similarity with another class of fields much used in algebraic geometry known as function fields of algebraic curves over finite fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] An example is $\mathbb {F} _{q}(T)$ , all of whose valuations are determined by where they send T to, as they extend the trivial (and only) valuation on $\mathbb {F} _{q}$ .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] They are similar in many respects, for example in that number rings are one-dimensional regular rings, as are the coordinate rings (the quotient fields of which are the function fields in question) of curves.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Therefore, both types of field are called global fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In accordance with the philosophy laid out above, they can be studied at a local level first, that is to say, by looking at the corresponding local fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For number fields K , the local fields are the completions of K at all places, including the archimedean ones (see local analysis).
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For function fields, the local fields are completions of the local rings at all points of the curve for function fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Many results valid for function fields also hold, at least if reformulated properly, for number fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] However, the study of number fields often poses difficulties and phenomena not encountered in function fields.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] For example, in function fields, there is no dichotomy into non-archimedean and archimedean places.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Nonetheless, function fields often serves as a source of intuition what should be expected in the number field case.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A prototypical question, posed at a global level, is whether some polynomial equation has a solution in K .
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] If this is the case, this solution is also a solution in all completions.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] The local-global principle or Hasse principle asserts that for quadratic equations, the converse holds, as well.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] Thereby, checking whether such an equation has a solution can be done on all the completions of K , which is often easier, since analytic methods (classical analytic tools such as intermediate value theorem at the archimedean places and p-adic analysis at the nonarchimedean places) can be used.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This implication does not hold, however, for more general types of equations.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] However, the idea of passing from local data to global ones proves fruitful in class field theory, for example, where local class field theory is used to obtain global insights mentioned above.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] This is also related to the fact that the Galois groups of the completions *K*v can be explicitly determined, whereas the Galois groups of global fields, even of $\mathbb {Q}$ are far less understood.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] In order to assemble local data pertaining to all local fields attached to K , the adele ring is set up.
[src:field-theory/algebraic-number-field] A multiplicative variant is referred to as ideles.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] In mathematics, particularly in algebra, a **field extension** is a pair of fields $K\subseteq L$ , such that the operations of *K* are those of *L* restricted to *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] In this case, *L* is an **extension field** of *K*, and *K* is a **subfield** of *L*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, under the usual notions of addition and multiplication, the complex numbers are an extension field of the real numbers; the real numbers are a subfield of the complex numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Field extensions are fundamental in algebraic number theory, and in the study of polynomial roots through Galois theory, and are widely used in algebraic geometry.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] A **subfield** K of a field L is a subset $K\subseteq L$ that is a field with respect to the field operations inherited from L .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Equivalently, a subfield is a subset that contains the multiplicative identity 1 , and is closed under the operations of addition, subtraction, multiplication, and taking the inverse of a nonzero element of K .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] As 1 – 1 = 0, the latter definition implies K and L have the same zero element.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, the field of rational numbers is a subfield of the real numbers, which is itself a subfield of the complex numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] More generally, the field of rational numbers is (or is isomorphic to) a subfield of any field of characteristic 0 .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The characteristic of a subfield is the same as the characteristic of the larger field.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] If K is a subfield of L , then L is an **extension field** or simply **extension** of K , and this pair of fields is a **field extension**.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Such a field extension is denoted $L/K$ (read as " L over K ").
[src:field-theory/field-extension] If L is an extension of F , which is in turn an extension of K , then F is said to be an **intermediate field** (or **intermediate extension** or **subextension**) of $L/K$ .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given a field extension $L/K$ , the larger field L is a K -vector space.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The dimension of this vector space is called the **degree** of the extension and is denoted by $[L:K]$ .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The degree of an extension is 1 if and only if the two fields are equal.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] In this case, the extension is a **trivial extension**.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Extensions of degree 2 and 3 are called **quadratic extensions** and **cubic extensions**, respectively.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] A **finite extension** is an extension that has a finite degree.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given two extensions $L/K$ and $M/L$ , the extension $M/K$ is finite if and only if both $L/K$ and $M/L$ are finite.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given a field extension $L/K$ and a subset S of L , there is a smallest subfield of L that contains K and S .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] It is the intersection of all subfields of L that contain K and S , and is denoted by $K(S)$ (read as " K *adjoin* S ").
[src:field-theory/field-extension] One says that $K(S)$ is the field *generated* by S over K , and that S is a generating set of $K(S)$ over K .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] If S consists of a single element s , the extension $K(s)/K$ is called a simple extension and s is called a primitive element of the extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An extension field of the form $K(S)$ is often said to result from the *adjunction* of S to K .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] In characteristic 0, every finite extension is a simple extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This is the primitive element theorem, which does not hold true for fields of non-zero characteristic.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] If a simple extension $K(s)/K$ is not finite, the field $K(s)$ is isomorphic to the field of rational fractions in s over K .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The notation *L* / *K* is purely formal and does not imply the formation of a quotient ring or quotient group or any other kind of division.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Instead the slash expresses the word "over".
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Some authors use the notations *L* : *K* or *L* | *K*, while others may simply indicate verbally that $L\supset K$ is a field extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Towers of extensions are often depicted diagrammatically.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Considering such a natural embedding as a field extension is an abuse of terminology that makes often the wording much simpler.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, there is a unique field homomorphism from ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠, the field rational numbers, into any field of characteristic 0, and one says commonly that every field of characteristic zero is an extension of ⁠ $\mathbb {Q}$ ⁠.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] On the other hand, there are two injective homomorphisms of the field ⁠ $K=\mathbb {Q} [X]/(X^{2}-X-1)$ ⁠ into ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠, which map ⁠ X ⁠ either to the golden ratio ⁠ $\omega ={\tfrac {1+{\sqrt {5}}}{2}}$ ⁠ or to ⁠ $-1/\omega$ ⁠.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Although the two homomorphisms have the same image, it would be confusing to say that ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ is an extension of ⁠ K ⁠.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Henceforth, we will consider field homomorphisms—always injective—as inclusions, when no confusion can arise.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The field of complex numbers $\mathbb {C}$ is an extension field of the field of real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ , and $\mathbb {R}$ in turn is an extension field of the field of rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Clearly then, $\mathbb {C} /\mathbb {Q}$ is also a field extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] We have $[\mathbb {C} :\mathbb {R} ]=2$ because $\{1,i\}$ is a basis, so the extension $\mathbb {C} /\mathbb {R}$ is finite.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This is a simple extension because $\mathbb {C} =\mathbb {R} (i).$ $[\mathbb {R} :\mathbb {Q} ]={\mathfrak {c}}$ (the cardinality of the continuum), so this extension is infinite.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] is an extension field of $\mathbb {Q} ,$ also clearly a simple extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The degree is 2 because $\left\{1,{\sqrt {2}}\right\}$ can serve as a basis.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] is an extension field of both $\mathbb {Q} ({\sqrt {2}})$ and $\mathbb {Q} ,$ of degree 2 and 4 respectively.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Finite extensions of $\mathbb {Q}$ are also called algebraic number fields and are important in number theory.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Another extension field of the rationals, which is also important in number theory, although not a finite extension, is the field of p-adic numbers $\mathbb {Q} _{p}$ for a prime number *p*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] It is common to construct an extension field of a given field *K* as a quotient ring of the polynomial ring *K*[*X*] in order to "create" a root for a given polynomial *f*(*X*).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Suppose for instance that *K* does not contain any element *x* with *x*2 = −1.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Then the polynomial $X^{2}+1$ is irreducible in *K*[*X*], consequently the ideal generated by this polynomial is maximal, and $L=K[X]/(X^{2}+1)$ is an extension field of *K* which *does* contain an element whose square is −1 (namely the residue class of *X*).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] By iterating the above construction, one can construct a splitting field of any polynomial from *K*[*X*].
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This is an extension field *L* of *K* in which the given polynomial splits into a product of linear factors.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] If *p* is any prime number and *n* is a positive integer, there is a unique (up to isomorphism) finite field $GF(p^{n})=\mathbb {F} _{p^{n}}$ with *pn* elements; this is an extension field of the prime field $\operatorname {GF} (p)=\mathbb {F} _{p}=\mathbb {Z} /p\mathbb {Z}$ with *p* elements.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given a field *K*, we can consider the field *K*(*X*) of all rational functions in the variable *X* with coefficients in *K*; the elements of *K*(*X*) are fractions of two polynomials over *K*, and indeed *K*(*X*) is the field of fractions of the polynomial ring *K*[*X*].
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This field of rational functions is an extension field of *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given a Riemann surface *M*, the set of all meromorphic functions defined on *M* is a field, denoted by $\mathbb {C} (M).$ It is a transcendental extension field of $\mathbb {C}$ if we identify every complex number with the corresponding constant function defined on *M*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] More generally, given an algebraic variety *V* over some field *K*, the function field *K*(*V*), consisting of the rational functions defined on *V*, is an extension field of *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An element *x* of a field extension $L/K$ is algebraic over *K* if it is a root of a nonzero polynomial with coefficients in *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, ${\sqrt {2}}$ is algebraic over the rational numbers, because it is a root of $x^{2}-2.$ If an element *x* of *L* is algebraic over *K*, the monic polynomial of lowest degree that has *x* as a root is called the minimal polynomial of *x*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This minimal polynomial is irreducible over *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An element *s* of *L* is algebraic over *K* if and only if the simple extension *K*(*s*) /*K* is a finite extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] In this case the degree of the extension equals the degree of the minimal polynomial, and a basis of the *K*-vector space *K*(*s*) consists of $1,s,s^{2},\ldots ,s^{d-1},$ where *d* is the degree of the minimal polynomial.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The set of the elements of *L* that are algebraic over *K* form a subextension, which is called the algebraic closure of *K* in *L*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This results from the preceding characterization: if *s* and *t* are algebraic, the extensions *K*(*s*) /*K* and *K*(*s*)(*t*) /*K*(*s*) are finite.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] It follows that *s* ± *t*, *st* and 1/*s* are all algebraic.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An *algebraic extension* $L/K$ is an extension such that every element of *L* is algebraic over *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Equivalently, an algebraic extension is an extension that is generated by algebraic elements.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] A simple extension is algebraic if and only if it is finite.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] This implies that an extension is algebraic if and only if it is the union of its finite subextensions, and that every finite extension is algebraic.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Every field *K* has an algebraic closure, which is up to an isomorphism the largest extension field of *K* which is algebraic over *K*, and also the smallest extension field such that every polynomial with coefficients in *K* has a root in it.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, $\mathbb {C}$ is an algebraic closure of $\mathbb {R}$ , but not an algebraic closure of $\mathbb {Q}$ , as it is not algebraic over $\mathbb {Q}$ (for example π is not algebraic over $\mathbb {Q}$ ).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given a field extension $L/K$ , a subset *S* of *L* is called algebraically independent over *K* if no non-trivial polynomial relation with coefficients in *K* exists among the elements of *S*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The largest cardinality of an algebraically independent set is called the transcendence degree of *L*/*K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] It is always possible to find a set *S*, algebraically independent over *K*, such that *L*/*K*(*S*) is algebraic.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Such a set *S* is called a transcendence basis of *L*/*K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] All transcendence bases have the same cardinality, equal to the transcendence degree of the extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An extension $L/K$ is said to be **purely transcendental** if and only if there exists a transcendence basis *S* of $L/K$ such that *L* = *K*(*S*).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Such an extension has the property that all elements of *L* except those of *K* are transcendental over *K*, but, however, there are extensions with this property which are not purely transcendental—a class of such extensions take the form *L*/*K* where both *L* and *K* are algebraically closed.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] If *L*/*K* is purely transcendental and *S* is a transcendence basis of the extension, it doesn't necessarily follow that *L* = *K*(*S*).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] On the opposite, even when one knows a transcendence basis, it may be difficult to decide whether the extension is purely separable, and if it is so, it may be difficult to find a transcendence basis *S* such that *L* = *K*(*S*).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Similarly, $\{y\}$ is a transcendence basis that does not generate the whole extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] However the extension is purely transcendental since, if one set $t=y/x,$ one has $x=t^{2}$ and $y=t^{3},$ and thus t generates the whole extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Purely transcendental extensions of an algebraically closed field occur as function fields of rational varieties.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The problem of finding a rational parametrization of a rational variety is equivalent with the problem of finding a transcendence basis that generates the whole extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An algebraic extension $L/K$ is called normal if every irreducible polynomial in *K*[*X*] that has a root in *L* completely factors into linear factors over *L*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Every algebraic extension *F*/*K* admits a normal closure *L*, which is an extension field of *F* such that $L/K$ is normal and which is minimal with this property.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] An algebraic extension $L/K$ is called separable if the minimal polynomial of every element of *L* over *K* is separable, i.e., has no repeated roots in an algebraic closure over *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] A Galois extension is a field extension that is both normal and separable.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] A consequence of the primitive element theorem states that every finite separable extension has a primitive element (i.e. is simple).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given any field extension $L/K$ , we can consider its **automorphism group** ${\text{Aut}}(L/K)$ , consisting of all field automorphisms *α*: *L* → *L* with *α*(*x*) = *x* for all *x* in *K*.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] When the extension is Galois this automorphism group is called the Galois group of the extension.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Extensions whose Galois group is abelian are called abelian extensions.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For a given field extension $L/K$ , one is often interested in the intermediate fields *F* (subfields of *L* that contain *K*).
[src:field-theory/field-extension] The significance of Galois extensions and Galois groups is that they allow a complete description of the intermediate fields: there is a bijection between the intermediate fields and the subgroups of the Galois group, described by the fundamental theorem of Galois theory.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Field extensions can be generalized to ring extensions which consist of a ring and one of its subrings.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] A closer non-commutative analog are central simple algebras (CSAs) – ring extensions over a field, which are simple algebra (no non-trivial 2-sided ideals, just as for a field) and where the center of the ring is exactly the field.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, the only finite field extension of the real numbers is the complex numbers, while the quaternions are a central simple algebra over the reals, and all CSAs over the reals are Brauer equivalent to the reals or the quaternions.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] CSAs can be further generalized to Azumaya algebras, where the base field is replaced by a commutative local ring.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Given a field extension, one can "extend scalars" on associated algebraic objects.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] For example, given a real vector space, one can produce a complex vector space via complexification.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] In addition to vector spaces, one can perform extension of scalars for associative algebras defined over the field, such as polynomials or group algebras and the associated group representations.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Extension of scalars of polynomials is often used implicitly, by just considering the coefficients as being elements of a larger field, but may also be considered more formally.
[src:field-theory/field-extension] Extension of scalars has numerous applications, as discussed in extension of scalars: applications.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **field** is a set on which addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division are defined and behave as the corresponding operations on rational numbers do.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A field is thus a fundamental algebraic structure that is widely used in algebra, number theory, and many other areas of mathematics.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The best known fields are the field of rational numbers, the field of real numbers, and the field of complex numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Many other fields, such as fields of rational functions, algebraic function fields, algebraic number fields, finite fields, and *p*-adic fields are commonly used and studied in mathematics, particularly in number theory and algebraic geometry.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The theory of fields proves that angle trisection and squaring the circle cannot be done with a compass and straightedge alone.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Galois theory, devoted to understanding the symmetries of field extensions, provides an elegant proof of the Abel–Ruffini theorem that general quintic equations cannot be solved in radicals.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Fields serve as foundational notions in several mathematical domains.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This includes different branches of mathematical analysis, which are based on fields with additional structure.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Basic theorems in analysis hinge on the structural properties of the field of real numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Most importantly for algebraic purposes, any field may be used as the scalars for a vector space, which is the standard general context for linear algebra.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Number fields, the siblings of the field of rational numbers, are studied in depth in number theory.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Function fields can help describe properties of geometric objects.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Finite fields are used for error correction codes and cryptography.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Informally, a field is a set with an addition operation *a* + *b* and a multiplication operation *a* ⋅ *b* that behave as they do for rational numbers and real numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The requirements include the existence of an additive inverse −*a* for each element a and of a multiplicative inverse *b*−1 for each nonzero element b.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This allows the definition of the so-called *inverse operations*, subtraction *a* − *b* and division *a* / *b*, as *a* − *b* = *a* + (−*b*) and *a* / *b* = *a* ⋅ *b*−1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Often the product *a* ⋅ *b* is represented by juxtaposition, as ab.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Formally, a field is a set F together with two binary operations on F, called *addition* and *multiplication*, satisfying the axioms given below.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A binary operation on F is a mapping *F* × *F* → *F*; it sends each ordered pair of elements of F to a uniquely determined element of F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The result of the addition of a and b is called the *sum* of a and b, and is denoted *a* + *b*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The result of the multiplication of a and b is called the *product* of a and b, and is denoted *a* ⋅ *b*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These operations are required to satisfy the following properties, called *field axioms*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Even more succinctly: a field is a commutative ring in which 0 ≠ 1 and all nonzero elements are invertible under multiplication.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Fields can also be defined in different, but equivalent, ways.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] One can alternatively define a field by four binary operations (addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division) and their required properties.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Division by zero is, by definition, excluded.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In order to avoid existential quantifiers, fields can be defined by two binary operations (addition and multiplication), two unary operations (yielding the additive and multiplicative inverses respectively), and two nullary operations (the constants 0 and 1).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These operations are then subject to the conditions above.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Avoiding existential quantifiers is important in constructive mathematics and computing.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] One may equivalently define a field by the same two binary operations, one unary operation (the multiplicative inverse), and two (not necessarily distinct) constants 1 and −1, since 0 = 1 + (−1) and −*a* = (−1)*a*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Rational numbers were widely used for a long time before the development of fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] They are numbers that can be written as fractions *a*/*b*, where a and b are integers, and *b* ≠ 0.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The abstractly required field axioms reduce to standard properties of rational numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The real numbers **R**, with the usual operations of addition and multiplication, also form a field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] where i is the imaginary unit, i.e., a (non-real) number satisfying *i*2 = −1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Addition and multiplication of real numbers are defined in such a way that expressions of this type satisfy all field axioms and thus hold for **C**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is immediate that this is again an expression of the above type, and so the complex numbers form a field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Complex numbers can be geometrically represented as points in the plane, with Cartesian coordinates given by the real numbers of their describing expression, or as the arrows from the origin to these points, specified by their length and an angle enclosed with some distinct direction.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Addition then corresponds to combining the arrows to the intuitive parallelogram (adding the Cartesian coordinates), and the multiplication is – less intuitively – combining rotating and scaling of the arrows (adding the angles and multiplying the lengths).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The fields of real and complex numbers are used throughout mathematics, physics, engineering, statistics, and many other scientific disciplines.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In antiquity, several geometric problems concerned the (in)feasibility of constructing certain numbers with compass and straightedge.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, it was unknown to the Greeks that it is, in general, impossible to trisect a given angle in this way.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These problems can be settled using the field of constructible numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Real constructible numbers are, by definition, lengths of line segments that can be constructed from the points 0 and 1 in finitely many steps using only compass and straightedge.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These numbers, endowed with the field operations of real numbers, restricted to the constructible numbers, form a field, which properly includes the field **Q** of rational numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The illustration shows the construction of square roots of constructible numbers, not necessarily contained within **Q**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Using the labeling in the illustration, construct the segments *AD*, *DB*, and a semicircle over *AB* (center at the midpoint O), which intersects the perpendicular line through D in a point C, at a distance of exactly $h={\sqrt {p}}$ from B when *BD* has length one.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It can be shown that ${\sqrt[{3}]{2}}$ is not a constructible number, which implies that it is impossible to construct with compass and straightedge the length of the side of a cube with volume 2, another problem posed by the ancient Greeks.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In addition to familiar number systems such as the rationals, there are other, less immediate examples of fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The following example is a field consisting of four elements called O, I, A, and B.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The notation is chosen such that O plays the role of the additive identity element (denoted 0 in the axioms above), and I is the multiplicative identity (denoted 1 in the axioms above).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The field axioms can be verified by using some more field theory, or by direct computation.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This field is called a finite field or **Galois field** with four elements, and is denoted **F**4 or GF(4).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The subset consisting of O and I (highlighted in red in the tables at the right) is also a field, known as the *binary field* **F**2 or GF(2).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In this section, F denotes an arbitrary field and a and b are arbitrary elements of F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This means that every field is an integral domain.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The axioms of a field F imply that it is an abelian group under addition.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This group is called the additive group of the field, and is sometimes denoted by (*F*, +) when denoting it simply as F could be confusing.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Similarly, the *nonzero* elements of F form an abelian group under multiplication, called the multiplicative group, and denoted by $(F\smallsetminus \{0\},\cdot )$ or just $F\smallsetminus \{0\}$ , or *F*×.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Some elementary statements about fields can therefore be obtained by applying general facts of groups.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the additive and multiplicative inverses −*a* and *a*−1 are uniquely determined by a.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The requirement 1 ≠ 0 is imposed by convention to exclude the trivial ring, which consists of a single element; indeed, the nonzero elements of the trivial ring (there are none) do not form a group, since a group must have at least one element.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Every finite subgroup of the multiplicative group of a field is cyclic (see *Root of unity § Cyclic groups*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] then F is said to have characteristic 0.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the field of rational numbers **Q** has characteristic 0 since no positive integer n is zero.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Otherwise, if there *is* a positive integer n satisfying this equation, the smallest such positive integer can be shown to be a prime number.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is usually denoted by p and the field is said to have characteristic p then.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the field **F**4 has characteristic 2 since (in the notation of the above addition table) *I* + *I* = O.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] If F has characteristic p, then *p* ⋅ *a* = 0 for all a in F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] since all other binomial coefficients appearing in the binomial formula are divisible by p.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Here, *a**p* := *a* ⋅ *a* ⋅ ⋯ ⋅ *a* (p factors) is the pth power, i.e., the p-fold product of the element a.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] is compatible with the addition in F (and also with the multiplication), and is therefore a field homomorphism.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The existence of this homomorphism makes fields in characteristic p quite different from fields of characteristic 0.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A *subfield* E of a field F is a subset of F that is a field with respect to the field operations of F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Equivalently E is a subset of F that contains 1, and is closed under addition, multiplication, additive inverse and multiplicative inverse of a nonzero element.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This means that 1 ∊ *E*, that for all *a*, *b* ∊ *E* both *a* + *b* and *a* ⋅ *b* are in E, and that for all *a* ≠ 0 in E, both −*a* and 1/*a* are in E.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] If *φ* is also surjective, it is called an isomorphism (or the fields E and F are called isomorphic).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A field is called a **prime field** if it has no proper (i.e., strictly smaller) subfields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] If the characteristic of F is p (a prime number), the prime field is isomorphic to the finite field **F***p* introduced below.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Otherwise the prime field is isomorphic to **Q**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The simplest finite fields, with prime order, are most directly accessible using modular arithmetic.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The addition and multiplication on this set are done by performing the operation in question in the set **Z** of integers, dividing by n and taking the remainder as result.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This construction yields a field precisely if n is a prime number.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, taking the prime *n* = 2 results in the above-mentioned field **F**2.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The field **Z**/*p***Z** with p elements (p being prime) constructed in this way is usually denoted by **F***p*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Every finite field F has *q* = *p**n* elements, where *p* is prime and *n* ≥ 1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This statement holds since F may be viewed as a vector space over its prime field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The dimension of this vector space is necessarily finite, say n, which implies the asserted statement.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Such a splitting field is an extension of **F***p* in which the polynomial f has q zeros.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This means f has as many zeros as possible since the degree of f is q.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For *q* = 22 = 4, it can be checked case by case using the above multiplication table that all four elements of **F**4 satisfy the equation *x*4 = *x*, so they are zeros of f.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] By contrast, in **F**2, f has only two zeros (namely 0 and 1), so f does not split into linear factors in this smaller field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Elaborating further on basic field-theoretic notions, it can be shown that two finite fields with the same order are isomorphic.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is thus customary to speak of *the* finite field with q elements, denoted by **F***q* or GF(*q*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Historically, three algebraic disciplines led to the concept of a field: the question of solving polynomial equations, algebraic number theory, and algebraic geometry.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] (with *ω* being a third root of unity) only yields two values.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This way, Lagrange conceptually explained the classical solution method of Scipione del Ferro and François Viète, which proceeds by reducing a cubic equation for an unknown x to a quadratic equation for *x*3.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Together with a similar observation for equations of degree 4, Lagrange thus linked what eventually became the concept of fields and the concept of groups.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] for a prime p and, again using modern language, the resulting cyclic Galois group.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Gauss deduced that a regular p-gon can be constructed if *p* = 22*k* + 1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Building on Lagrange's work, Paolo Ruffini claimed (1799) that quintic equations (polynomial equations of degree 5) cannot be solved algebraically; however, his arguments were incomplete.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These gaps were filled by Niels Henrik Abel in 1824. Évariste Galois, in 1832, devised necessary and sufficient criteria for a polynomial equation to be algebraically solvable, thus establishing in effect what is known as Galois theory today.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Both Abel and Galois worked with what is today called an algebraic number field, but they conceived neither an explicit notion of a field, nor of a group.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In 1871 Richard Dedekind introduced, for a set of real or complex numbers that is closed under the four arithmetic operations, the German word *Körper*, which means "body" or "corpus" (to suggest an organically closed entity).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The English term "field" was introduced by Moore (1893).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In 1881 Leopold Kronecker defined what he called a *domain of rationality*, which is a field of rational fractions in modern terms.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Kronecker's notion did not cover the field of all algebraic numbers (which is a field in Dedekind's sense), but on the other hand was more abstract than Dedekind's in that it made no specific assumption on the nature of the elements of a field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Kronecker interpreted a field such as **Q**(π) abstractly as the rational function field **Q**(*X*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Before this examples of transcendental numbers were known since Joseph Liouville's work in 1844, until Charles Hermite (1873) and Ferdinand von Lindemann (1882) proved the transcendence of e and *π*, respectively.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The first clear definition of an abstract field is due to Weber (1893).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In particular, Heinrich Martin Weber's notion included the field **F***p*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Giuseppe Veronese (1891) studied the field of formal power series, which led Hensel (1904) to introduce the field of p-adic numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Steinitz (1910) synthesized the knowledge of abstract field theory accumulated so far.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] He axiomatically studied the properties of fields and defined many important field-theoretic concepts.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The majority of the theorems mentioned in the sections Galois theory, Constructing fields and Elementary notions can be found in Steinitz's work.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Artin & Schreier (1927) linked the notion of orderings in a field, and thus the area of analysis, to purely algebraic properties.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Emil Artin redeveloped Galois theory from 1928 through 1942, eliminating the dependency on the primitive element theorem.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A commutative ring is a set that is equipped with an addition and multiplication operation and satisfies all the axioms of a field, except for the existence of multiplicative inverses *a*−1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the integers **Z** form a commutative ring, but not a field: the reciprocal of an integer n is not itself an integer, unless *n* = ±1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In the hierarchy of algebraic structures fields can be characterized as the commutative rings R in which every nonzero element is a unit (which means every element is invertible).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Similarly, fields are the commutative rings with precisely two distinct ideals, (0) and R.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Fields are also precisely the commutative rings in which (0) is the only prime ideal.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Given a commutative ring R, there are two ways to construct a field related to R, i.e., two ways of modifying R such that all nonzero elements become invertible: forming the field of fractions, and forming residue fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The field of fractions of **Z** is **Q**, the rationals, while the residue fields of **Z** are the finite fields **F***p*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Given an integral domain R, its field of fractions *Q*(*R*) is built with the fractions of two elements of R exactly as **Q** is constructed from the integers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] More precisely, the elements of *Q*(*R*) are the fractions *a*/*b* where a and b are in R, and *b* ≠ 0.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Two fractions *a*/*b* and *c*/*d* are equal if and only if *ad* = *bc*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The operation on the fractions work exactly as for rational numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is straightforward to show that, if the ring is an integral domain, the set of the fractions form a field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The field *F*(*x*) of the rational fractions over a field (or an integral domain) F is the field of fractions of the polynomial ring *F*[*x*].
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] over a field F is the field of fractions of the ring *F*[[*x*]] of formal power series (in which *k* ≥ 0).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Since any Laurent series is a fraction of a power series divided by a power of x (as opposed to an arbitrary power series), the representation of fractions is less important in this situation, though.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In addition to the field of fractions, which embeds R injectively into a field, a field can be obtained from a commutative ring R by means of a surjective map onto a field F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Any field obtained in this way is a quotient *R* / *m*, where m is a maximal ideal of R.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] If R has only one maximal ideal m, this field is called the residue field of R.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The ideal generated by a single polynomial f in the polynomial ring *R* = *E*[*X*] (over a field E) is maximal if and only if f is irreducible in E, i.e., if f cannot be expressed as the product of two polynomials in *E*[*X*] of smaller degree.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, **C** is obtained from **R** by adjoining the imaginary unit symbol i, which satisfies *f*(*i*) = 0, where *f*(*X*) = *X*2 + 1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Fields can be constructed inside a given bigger container field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Suppose given a field E, and a field F containing E as a subfield.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For any element x of F, there is a smallest subfield of F containing E and x, called the subfield of *F* generated by x and denoted *E*(*x*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The passage from E to *E*(*x*) is referred to by *adjoining an element* to E.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] More generally, for a subset *S* ⊂ *F*, there is a minimal subfield of F containing E and S, denoted by *E*(*S*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The compositum of two subfields E and *E*′ of some field F is the smallest subfield of F containing both E and *E*′.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The compositum can be used to construct the biggest subfield of F satisfying a certain property, for example the biggest subfield of F, which is, in the language introduced below, algebraic over E.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A basic datum of a field extension is its degree [*F* : *E*], i.e., the dimension of F as an E-vector space.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Extensions whose degree is finite are referred to as finite extensions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A pivotal notion in the study of field extensions *F* / *E* are algebraic elements.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A field extension in which every element of F is algebraic over E is called an algebraic extension.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Any finite extension is necessarily algebraic, as can be deduced from the above multiplicativity formula.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The subfield *E*(*x*) generated by an element x, as above, is an algebraic extension of E if and only if x is an algebraic element.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] That is to say, if x is algebraic, all other elements of *E*(*x*) are necessarily algebraic as well.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Moreover, the degree of the extension *E*(*x*) / *E*, i.e., the dimension of *E*(*x*) as an E-vector space, equals the minimal degree n such that there is a polynomial equation involving x, as above.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The above-mentioned field of rational fractions *E*(*X*), where X is an indeterminate, is not an algebraic extension of E since there is no polynomial equation with coefficients in E whose zero is X.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Elements, such as X, which are not algebraic are called transcendental.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Informally speaking, the indeterminate X and its powers do not interact with elements of E.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A similar construction can be carried out with a set of indeterminates, instead of just one.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Once again, the field extension *E*(*x*) / *E* discussed above is a key example: if x is not algebraic (i.e., x is not a root of a polynomial with coefficients in E), then *E*(*x*) is isomorphic to *E*(*X*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This isomorphism is obtained by substituting x to X in rational fractions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A subset S of a field F is a transcendence basis if it is algebraically independent (do not satisfy any polynomial relations) over E and if F is an algebraic extension of *E*(*S*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Any field extension *F* / *E* has a transcendence basis.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Thus, field extensions can be split into ones of the form *E*(*S*) / *E* (purely transcendental extensions) and algebraic extensions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] By the fundamental theorem of algebra, **C** is algebraically closed, i.e., *any* polynomial equation with complex coefficients has a complex solution.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] does not have any rational or real solution.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A field containing F is called an *algebraic closure* of F if it is algebraic over F (roughly speaking, not too big compared to F) and is algebraically closed (big enough to contain solutions of all polynomial equations).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] By the above, **C** is an algebraic closure of **R**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is rather special for the algebraic closure of some field F to be a finite extension of F, because by the Artin–Schreier theorem, the degree of this extension is necessarily 2, and F is elementarily equivalent to **R**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Such fields are also known as real closed fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Any field F has an algebraic closure, which is moreover unique up to (non-unique) isomorphism.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is commonly referred to as *the* algebraic closure and denoted *F*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the algebraic closure **Q** of **Q** is called the field of algebraic numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The field *F* is usually rather implicit since its construction requires the ultrafilter lemma, a set-theoretic axiom that is weaker than the axiom of choice.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In this regard, the algebraic closure of **F***q*, is exceptionally simple.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is the union of the finite fields containing **F***q* (the ones of order *q**n*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For any algebraically closed field F of characteristic 0, the algebraic closure of the field *F*((*t*)) of Laurent series is the field of Puiseux series, obtained by adjoining roots of t.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Since fields are ubiquitous in mathematics and beyond, several refinements of the concept have been adapted to the needs of particular mathematical areas.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A field *F* is called an *ordered field* if any two elements can be compared, so that *x* + *y* ≥ 0 and *xy* ≥ 0 whenever *x* ≥ 0 and *y* ≥ 0.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the real numbers form an ordered field, with the usual ordering ≥.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The set of all possible orders on a fixed field F is isomorphic to the set of ring homomorphisms from the Witt ring W(*F*) of quadratic forms over F, to **Z**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] whose value is greater than that element, that is, there are no infinite elements.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Equivalently, the field contains no infinitesimals (elements smaller than all rational numbers); or, yet equivalent, the field is isomorphic to a subfield of **R**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] An ordered field is Dedekind-complete if all upper bounds, lower bounds (see *Dedekind cut*) and limits, which should exist, do exist.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] More formally, each bounded subset of F is required to have a least upper bound.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Any complete field is necessarily Archimedean, since in any non-Archimedean field there is neither a greatest infinitesimal nor a least positive rational, whence the sequence 1/2, 1/3, 1/4, ..., every element of which is greater than every infinitesimal, has no limit.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Since every proper subfield of the reals also contains such gaps, **R** is the unique complete ordered field, up to isomorphism.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Several foundational results in calculus follow directly from this characterization of the reals.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The hyperreals **R*** form an ordered field that is not Archimedean.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] It is an extension of the reals obtained by including infinite and infinitesimal numbers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These are larger, respectively smaller than any real number.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The hyperreals form the foundational basis of non-standard analysis.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Another refinement of the notion of a field is a **topological field**, in which the set F is a topological space, such that all operations of the field (addition, multiplication, the maps *a* ↦ −*a* and *a* ↦ *a*−1) are continuous maps with respect to the topology of the space.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] that measures a *distance* between any two elements of F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The completion of F is another field in which, informally speaking, the "gaps" in the original field F are filled, if there are any.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, any irrational number x, such as *x* = √2, is a "gap" in the field **Q** of the rational numbers, in the sense that it is not in **Q** but there are rational numbers that are arbitrarily close to it for the distance given by the absolute value.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The *completion* of **Q** for the metric defined by the absolute value is the field of the real numbers **R**, and the construction of the real numbers through Cauchy sequences consists essentially of introducing new numbers for filling all such gaps.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The field **Q***p* is used in number theory and p-adic analysis.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The algebraic closure **Q***p* carries a unique norm extending the one on **Q***p*, but is not complete.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The completion of this algebraic closure, however, is algebraically closed.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Because of its rough analogy to the complex numbers, it is sometimes called the *complex p-adic numbers* and is denoted **C***p*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These two types of local fields share some fundamental similarities.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In this relation, the elements *p* ∈ **Q***p* and *t* ∈ **F***p*((*t*)) (referred to as the uniformizer) correspond to each other.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The first manifestation of this is at an elementary level: the elements of both fields can be expressed as power series in the uniformizer, with coefficients in **F***p*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Differential fields are fields equipped with a derivation, that is, an operator **D** such that $\mathbf {D} (ab)=\mathbf {D} (a)b+a\mathbf {D} (b)$ for all elements a and b of the field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the field **R**(*X*), together with the standard derivative operator **D** on polynomials, forms a differential field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] These fields are central to differential Galois theory, a variant of Galois theory dealing with linear differential equations.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Galois theory studies algebraic extensions of a field by studying the symmetry in the arithmetic operations of addition and multiplication.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] An important notion in this area is that of finite Galois extensions *F* / *E*, which are, by definition, those that are separable and normal.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] where f is an irreducible polynomial (as above).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For such an extension, being normal and separable means that all zeros of f are contained in F and that f has only simple zeros.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The latter condition is always satisfied if E has characteristic 0.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For a finite Galois extension, the Galois group Gal(*F*/*E*) is the group of field automorphisms of F that are trivial on E (i.e., the bijections *σ* : *F* → *F* that preserve addition and multiplication and that send elements of E to themselves).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The importance of this group stems from the fundamental theorem of Galois theory, which constructs an explicit one-to-one correspondence between the set of subgroups of Gal(*F*/*E*) and the set of intermediate extensions of the extension *F*/*E*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] By means of this correspondence, group-theoretic properties translate into facts about fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, if the Galois group of a Galois extension as above is not solvable (cannot be built from abelian groups), then the zeros of f *cannot* be expressed in terms of addition, multiplication, and radicals, i.e., expressions involving ${\sqrt[{n}]{~}}$ .
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the symmetric groups S*n* is not solvable for *n* ≥ 5.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Consequently, as can be shown, the zeros of the following polynomials are not expressible by sums, products, and radicals.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The tensor product of fields is not usually a field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This fact is the beginning of Grothendieck's Galois theory, a far-reaching extension of Galois theory applicable to algebro-geometric objects.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Basic invariants of a field F include the characteristic and the transcendence degree of F over its prime field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The latter is defined as the maximal number of elements in F that are algebraically independent over the prime field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Two algebraically closed fields E and F are isomorphic precisely if these two data agree.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] This implies that any two uncountable algebraically closed fields of the same cardinality and the same characteristic are isomorphic.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, **Q***p*, **C***p* and **C** are isomorphic (but *not* isomorphic as topological fields).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In model theory, a branch of mathematical logic, two fields E and F are called elementarily equivalent if every mathematical statement that is true for E is also true for F and conversely.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The mathematical statements in question are required to be first-order sentences (involving 0, 1, the addition and multiplication).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The set of such formulas for all n expresses that E is algebraically closed.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The Lefschetz principle states that **C** is elementarily equivalent to any algebraically closed field F of characteristic zero.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Moreover, any fixed statement *φ* holds in **C** if and only if it holds in any algebraically closed field of sufficiently high characteristic.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] If U is an ultrafilter on a set I, and *F**i* is a field for every i in I, the ultraproduct of the *F**i* with respect to U is a field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] since it behaves in several ways as a limit of the fields *F**i*: Łoś's theorem states that any first order statement that holds for all but finitely many *F**i*, also holds for the ultraproduct.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In addition, model theory also studies the logical properties of various other types of fields, such as real closed fields or exponential fields (which are equipped with an exponential function exp : *F* → *F*×).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For fields that are not algebraically closed (or not separably closed), the absolute Galois group Gal(*F*) is fundamentally important: extending the case of finite Galois extensions outlined above, this group governs *all* finite separable extensions of F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] By elementary means, the group Gal(**F***q*) can be shown to be the Prüfer group, the profinite completion of **Z**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] A description in terms of generators and relations is also known for the Galois groups of p-adic number fields (finite extensions of **Q***p*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Representations of Galois groups and of related groups such as the Weil group are fundamental in many branches of arithmetic, such as the Langlands program.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] The cohomological study of such representations is done using Galois cohomology.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Algebraic K-theory is related to the group of invertible matrices with coefficients the given field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] For example, the process of taking the determinant of an invertible matrix leads to an isomorphism *K*1(*F*) = *F*×.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] Matsumoto's theorem shows that *K*2(*F*) agrees with *K*2*M*(*F*).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p01] In higher degrees, K-theory diverges from Milnor K-theory and remains hard to compute in general.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] has a unique solution x in a field F, namely $x=a^{-1}b.$ This immediate consequence of the definition of a field is fundamental in linear algebra.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For example, it is an essential ingredient of Gaussian elimination and of the proof that any vector space has a basis.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The theory of modules (the analogue of vector spaces over rings instead of fields) is much more complicated, because the above equation may have several or no solutions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] In particular systems of linear equations over a ring are much more difficult to solve than in the case of fields, even in the specially simple case of the ring **Z** of the integers.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Finite fields are also used in coding theory and combinatorics.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] This makes these functions a F-commutative algebra.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For having a *field* of functions, one must consider algebras of functions that are integral domains.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] form a field, called field of functions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] In this case, one considers the algebra of holomorphic functions, i.e., complex-valued differentiable functions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Their ratios form the field of meromorphic functions on X.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The function field of an algebraic variety X (a geometric object defined as the common zeros of polynomial equations) consists of ratios of regular functions, i.e., ratios of polynomial functions on the variety.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For example, the function field of the n-dimensional vector space Fn over a field F is *F*(*x*1, ..., *x**n*): the field consisting of ratios of polynomials in n indeterminates over F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The function field of X is the same as the one of any open dense subvariety.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] In other words, the function field is insensitive to replacing X by a (slightly) smaller subvariety.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The function field is invariant under isomorphism and birational equivalence of varieties.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] It is therefore an important tool for the study of abstract algebraic varieties and for the classification of algebraic varieties.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For example, the dimension, which equals the transcendence degree of *F*(*X*), is invariant under birational equivalence.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For curves (i.e., the dimension is one), the function field *F*(*X*) is very close to X: if X is smooth and proper (the analogue of being compact), X can be reconstructed, up to isomorphism, from its field of functions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] In higher dimension the function field remembers less, but still decisive information about X.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The study of function fields and their geometric meaning in higher dimensions is referred to as birational geometry.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The minimal model program attempts to identify the simplest (in a certain precise sense) algebraic varieties with a prescribed function field.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Global fields are in the limelight in algebraic number theory and arithmetic geometry.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] They are, by definition, number fields (finite extensions of **Q**) or function fields over **F***q* (finite extensions of **F***q*(*t*)).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] As for local fields, these two types of fields share several similar features, even though they are of characteristic 0 and positive characteristic, respectively.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] This function field analogy can help to shape mathematical expectations, often first by understanding questions about function fields, and later treating the number field case.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For example, the Riemann hypothesis concerning the zeros of the Riemann zeta function (open as of 2017) can be regarded as being parallel to the Weil conjectures (proven in 1974 by Pierre Deligne).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Cyclotomic fields are among the most intensely studied number fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] They are of the form **Q**(*ζ**n*), where *ζ**n* is a primitive nth root of unity, i.e., a complex number *ζ* that satisfies *ζ**n* = 1 and *ζ**m* ≠ 1 for all 0 < *m* < *n*.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Local fields are completions of global fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Ostrowski's theorem asserts that the only completions of **Q**, a global field, are the local fields **Q***p* and **R**.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Studying arithmetic questions in global fields may sometimes be done by looking at the corresponding questions locally.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] This technique is called the local–global principle.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For example, the Hasse–Minkowski theorem reduces the problem of finding rational solutions of quadratic equations to solving these equations in **R** and **Q***p*, whose solutions can easily be described.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Unlike for local fields, the Galois groups of global fields are not known.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Inverse Galois theory studies the (unsolved) problem whether any finite group is the Galois group Gal(*F*/**Q**) for some number field F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Class field theory describes the abelian extensions, i.e., ones with abelian Galois group, or equivalently the abelianized Galois groups of global fields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] obtained by adjoining all primitive nth roots of unity.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Kronecker's Jugendtraum asks for a similarly explicit description of *F*ab of general number fields F.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For imaginary quadratic fields, $F=\mathbf {Q} ({\sqrt {-d}})$ , *d* > 0, the theory of complex multiplication describes *F*ab using elliptic curves.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] For general number fields, no such explicit description is known.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] In addition to the additional structure that fields may enjoy, fields admit various other related notions.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Since in any field 0 ≠ 1, any field has at least two elements.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Nonetheless, there is a concept of field with one element, which is suggested to be a limit of the finite fields **F***p*, as p tends to 1.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] In addition to division rings, there are various other weaker algebraic structures related to fields such as quasifields, near-fields and semifields.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] There are also proper classes with field structure, which are sometimes called **Field**s, with a capital 'F'.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The surreal numbers form a Field containing the reals, and would be a field except for the fact that they are a proper class, not a set.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The nimbers, a concept from game theory, form such a Field as well.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Dropping one or several axioms in the definition of a field leads to other algebraic structures.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] As was mentioned above, commutative rings satisfy all field axioms except for the existence of multiplicative inverses.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Dropping instead commutativity of multiplication leads to the concept of a *division ring* or *skew field*; sometimes associativity is weakened as well.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Historically, division rings were sometimes referred to as "fields", while fields were called "commutative fields".
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The only division rings that are finite-dimensional **R**-vector spaces are **R** itself, **C** (which is a field), and the quaternions **H** (in which multiplication is non-commutative).
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] This result is known as the Frobenius theorem.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] The octonions **O**, for which multiplication is neither commutative nor associative, is a normed alternative division algebra, but is not a division ring.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] This fact was proved using methods of algebraic topology in 1958 by Michel Kervaire, Raoul Bott, and John Milnor.
[src:field-theory/field-mathematics-p02] Wedderburn's little theorem states that all finite division rings are fields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In mathematics, a **finite field** or **Galois field** (so-named in honor of Évariste Galois) is a field that has a finite number of elements.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As with any field, a finite field is a set on which the operations of multiplication, addition, subtraction and division are defined and satisfy certain basic rules.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The most common examples of finite fields are the integers mod p when p is a prime number.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The *order* of a finite field is its number of elements, which is either a prime number or a prime power.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For every prime number p and every positive integer k there are fields of order $p^{k}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] All finite fields of a given order are isomorphic.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Finite fields are fundamental in a number of areas of mathematics and computer science, including number theory, algebraic geometry, Galois theory, finite geometry, cryptography and coding theory.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] A finite field is a field that is a finite set; this means that it has a finite number of elements on which multiplication, addition, subtraction and division (excluding division by zero) are defined and satisfy the field axioms.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The number of elements of a finite field is called its *order* or, sometimes, its *size*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] A finite field of order q exists if and only if q is a prime power $p^{k}$ (where p is a prime number and k is a positive integer).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In a field of order $p^{k}$ , summing p copies of any element always results in zero; that is, the characteristic of the field is p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For $q=p^{k}$ , all fields of order q are isomorphic (see *§ Existence and uniqueness* below).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Moreover, a field cannot contain two different finite subfields with the same order.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] One may therefore identify all finite fields with the same order, and they are unambiguously denoted $\mathbb {F} _{q}$ , $\mathbf {F} _{q}$ or $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ , where the letters GF stand for "Galois field".
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In a finite field of order q , the polynomial $X^{q}-X$ has all q elements of the finite field as roots.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The non-zero elements of a finite field form a multiplicative group.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This group is cyclic, so all non-zero elements can be expressed as powers of a single element called a primitive element of the field.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The simplest examples of finite fields are the fields of prime order: for each prime number p , the prime field of order p may be constructed as the integers modulo p , $\mathbb {Z} /p\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The elements of the prime field of order p may be represented by integers in the range $0,\ldots ,p-1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The sum, the difference and the product are the remainder of the division by p of the result of the corresponding integer operation.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The multiplicative inverse of an element may be computed by using the extended Euclidean algorithm (see *Modular multiplicative inverse § Extended Euclidean algorithm*).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For any element x in F and any integer n , denote by $n\cdot x$ the sum of n copies of x .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The least positive n such that $n\cdot 1=0$ is the characteristic p of the field.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This allows defining a multiplication $(k,x)\mapsto k\cdot x$ of an element k of $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ by an element x of F by choosing an integer representative for k .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This multiplication makes F into a $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ -vector space.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It follows that the number of elements of F is $p^{n}$ for some integer n .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The identity $(x+y)^{p}=x^{p}+y^{p}$ (sometimes called the freshman's dream) is true in a field of characteristic p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This follows from the binomial theorem, as each binomial coefficient of the expansion of $(x+y)^{p}$ , except the first and the last, is a multiple of p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] By Fermat's little theorem, if p is a prime number and x is in the field $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ then $x^{p}=x$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This implies the equality $X^{p}-X=\prod _{a\in \mathrm {GF} (p)}(X-a)$ for polynomials over $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] More generally, every element in $\mathrm {GF} (p^{n})$ satisfies the polynomial equation $x^{p^{n}}-x=0$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Any finite field extension of a finite field is separable and simple.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] That is, if E is a finite field and F is a subfield of E , then E is obtained from F by adjoining a single element whose minimal polynomial is separable.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] To use a piece of jargon, finite fields are perfect.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Finite fields are quasi-algebraically closed: every degree d homogeneous polynomial in n variables over a finite field with $n>d>0$ has a nontrivial zero.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This was a conjecture of Artin and Dickson, and was proved by Chevalley; see *Chevalley–Warning theorem*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Let $q=p^{n}$ be a prime power, and F be the splitting field of the polynomial $P=X^{q}-X$ over the prime field $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This means that F is a finite field of lowest order, in which P has q distinct roots (the formal derivative of P is $P'=-1$ , implying that $\mathrm {gcd} (P,P')=1$ , which in general implies that the splitting field is a separable extension of the original).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The above identity shows that the sum and the product of two roots of P are roots of P , as well as the multiplicative inverse of a root of P .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In other words, the roots of P form a field of order q , which is equal to F by the minimality of the splitting field.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The uniqueness up to isomorphism of splitting fields implies thus that all fields of order q are isomorphic.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Also, if a field F has a field of order $q=p^{k}$ as a subfield, its elements are the q roots of $X^{q}-X$ , and F cannot contain another subfield of order q .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In summary, we have the following classification theorem first proved in 1893 by E.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It follows that $\mathrm {GF} (p^{n})$ contains a subfield isomorphic to $\mathrm {GF} (p^{m})$ if and only if m is a divisor of n ; in that case, this subfield is unique.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In fact, the polynomial $X^{p^{m}}-X$ divides $X^{p^{n}}-X$ if and only if m is a divisor of n .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Given a prime power $q=p^{n}$ with p prime and $n>1$ , the field $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ may be explicitly constructed in the following way.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] One first chooses an irreducible polynomial P in $\mathrm {GF} (p)[X]$ of degree n (such an irreducible polynomial always exists).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Then the quotient ring $\mathrm {GF} (q)=\mathrm {GF} (p)[X]/(P)$ of the polynomial ring $\mathrm {GF} (p)[X]$ by the principal ideal generated by P is a field of order q .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] More explicitly, the elements of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ are the polynomials over $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ whose degree is strictly less than n .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The addition and the subtraction are those of polynomials over $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The product of two elements is the remainder of the Euclidean division by P of the product in $\mathrm {GF} (p)[X]$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The multiplicative inverse of a non-zero element may be computed with the extended Euclidean algorithm; see *Extended Euclidean algorithm § Simple algebraic field extensions*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] However, with this representation, elements of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ may be difficult to distinguish from the corresponding polynomials.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Therefore, it is common to give a name, commonly $\alpha$ to the element of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ that corresponds to the polynomial X .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Except in the construction of $\mathrm {GF} (4)$ , there are several possible choices for P , which produce isomorphic results.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] To simplify the Euclidean division, one commonly chooses for P a polynomial of the form $X^{n}+aX+b,$ which make the needed Euclidean divisions very efficient.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] However, for some fields, typically in characteristic 2 , irreducible polynomials of the form $X^{n}+aX+b$ may not exist.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In characteristic 2 , if the polynomial $X^{n}+X+1$ is reducible, it is recommended to choose $X^{n}+X^{k}+1$ with the lowest possible k that makes the polynomial irreducible.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If all these trinomials are reducible, one chooses "pentanomials" $X^{n}+X^{a}+X^{b}+X^{c}+1$ , as polynomials of degree greater than 1 , with an even number of terms, are never irreducible in characteristic 2 , having 1 as a root.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] A possible choice for such a polynomial is given by Conway polynomials.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] They ensure a certain compatibility between the representation of a field and the representations of its subfields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In the next sections, we will show how the general construction method outlined above works for small finite fields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] See below for the complete operation tables.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This may be deduced as follows from the results of the preceding section.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This implies that $\alpha ^{2}=1+\alpha ,$ and that $\alpha$ and $1+\alpha$ are the elements of $\mathrm {GF} (4)$ that are not in $\mathrm {GF} (2)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] A table for subtraction is not given, because subtraction is identical to addition, as is the case for every field of characteristic 2.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] To divide, multiply by the reciprocal: ⁠ $x/y=x\cdot (1/y)$ ⁠.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As in any field, division by zero is undefined.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] From the tables, it can be seen that the additive structure of $\mathrm {GF} (4)$ is isomorphic to the Klein four-group, while the non-zero multiplicative structure is isomorphic to the group $Z_{3}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The map $\varphi :x\mapsto x^{2}$ is the non-trivial field automorphism, called the Frobenius automorphism, which sends $\alpha$ into the second root $1+\alpha$ of the above-mentioned irreducible polynomial $X^{2}+X+1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For applying the above general construction of finite fields in the case of $\mathrm {GF} (p^{2})$ , one has to find an irreducible polynomial of degree 2.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For $p=2$ , this has been done in the preceding section.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If p is an odd prime, there are always irreducible polynomials of the form $X^{2}-r$ , with r in $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] More precisely, the polynomial $X^{2}-r$ is irreducible over $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ if and only if r is a quadratic non-residue modulo p (this is almost the definition of a quadratic non-residue).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] There are ${\frac {p-1}{2}}$ quadratic non-residues modulo p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For example, 2 is a quadratic non-residue for $p=3,5,11,13,\ldots$ , and 3 is a quadratic non-residue for $p=5,7,17,\ldots$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If $p\equiv 3\mod 4$ , that is $p=3,7,11,19,\ldots$ , one may choose $-1\equiv p-1$ as a quadratic non-residue, which allows us to have a very simple irreducible polynomial $X^{2}+1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Having chosen a quadratic non-residue r , let $\alpha$ be a symbolic square root of r , that is, a symbol that has the property $\alpha ^{2}=r$ , in the same way that the complex number i is a symbolic square root of $-1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Then, the elements of $\mathrm {GF} (p^{2})$ are all the linear expressions $a+b\alpha ,$ with a and b in $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The polynomial $X^{3}-X-1$ is irreducible over $\mathrm {GF} (2)$ and $\mathrm {GF} (3)$ , that is, it is irreducible modulo 2 and 3 (to show this, it suffices to show that it has no root in $\mathrm {GF} (2)$ nor in $\mathrm {GF} (3)$ , as if a cubic factors then it must contain a linear factor).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The polynomial $X^{4}+X+1$ is irreducible over $\mathrm {GF} (2)$ , that is, it is irreducible modulo 2 .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As the characteristic of $\mathrm {GF} (2)$ is 2 , each element is its additive inverse in $\mathrm {GF} (16)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The field $\mathrm {GF} (16)$ has eight primitive elements (the elements that have all nonzero elements of $\mathrm {GF} (16)$ as integer powers).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] These elements are the four roots of $X^{4}+X+1$ and their multiplicative inverses.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In particular, $\alpha$ is a primitive element, and the primitive elements are $\alpha ^{m}$ with m less than and coprime with $15$ (that is, 1, 2, 4, 7, 8, 11, 13, 14).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The set of non-zero elements in $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ is an abelian group under the multiplication, of order $q-1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] By Lagrange's theorem, there exists a divisor k of $q-1$ such that $x^{k}=1$ for every non-zero x in $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As the equation $x^{k}=1$ has at most k solutions in any field, $q-1$ is the lowest possible value for k .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The structure theorem of finite abelian groups implies that this multiplicative group is cyclic, that is, all non-zero elements are powers of a single element.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Such an element a is called a primitive element of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Unless $q=2,3$ , the primitive element is not unique.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The number of primitive elements is $\phi (q-1)$ where $\phi$ is Euler's totient function.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The result above implies that $x^{q}=x$ for every x in $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The particular case where q is prime is Fermat's little theorem.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If a is a primitive element in $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ , then for any non-zero element x in F , there is a unique integer n with $0\leq n\leq q-2$ such that $x=a^{n}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This integer n is called the discrete logarithm of x to the base a .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] While $a^{n}$ can be computed very quickly, for example using exponentiation by squaring, there is no known efficient algorithm for computing the inverse operation, the discrete logarithm.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This has been used in various cryptographic protocols, see *Discrete logarithm* for details.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] When the nonzero elements of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ are represented by their discrete logarithms, multiplication and division are easy, as they reduce to addition and subtraction modulo $q-1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] However, addition amounts to computing the discrete logarithm of $a^{m}+a^{n}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The identity $a^{m}+a^{n}=a^{n}\left(a^{m-n}+1\right)$ allows one to solve this problem by constructing the table of the discrete logarithms of $a^{n}+1$ , called Zech's logarithms, for $n=0,\ldots ,q-2$ (it is convenient to define the discrete logarithm of zero as being $-\infty$ ).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Zech's logarithms are useful for large computations, such as linear algebra over medium-sized fields, that is, fields that are sufficiently large for making natural algorithms inefficient, but not too large, as one has to pre-compute a table of the same size as the order of the field.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Every nonzero element of a finite field is a root of unity, as $x^{q-1}=1$ for every nonzero element of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If n is a positive integer, an n th **primitive root of unity** is a solution of the equation $x^{n}=1$ that is not a solution of the equation $x^{m}=1$ for any positive integer $m<n$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If a is a n th primitive root of unity in a field F , then F contains all the n roots of unity, which are $1,a,a^{2},\ldots ,a^{n-1}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The field $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ contains a n th primitive root of unity if and only if n is a divisor of $q-1$ ; if n is a divisor of $q-1$ , then the number of primitive n th roots of unity in $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ is $\phi (n)$ (Euler's totient function).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The number of n th roots of unity in $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ is $\mathrm {gcd} (n,q-1)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In a field of characteristic p , the Frobenius endomorphism $\varphi (x)=x^{p}$ is injective.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This show that every $np$ th root of unity is also a n th root of unity.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It follows that primitive $np$ th roots of unity never exist in a field of characteristic p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] On the other hand, if n is coprime to p , the roots of the n th cyclotomic polynomial are distinct in every field of characteristic p , as this polynomial is a divisor of $X^{n}-1$ , whose discriminant $n^{n}$ is nonzero modulo p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It follows that the n th cyclotomic polynomial factors over $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ into distinct irreducible polynomials that have all the same degree, say d , and that $\mathrm {GF} (p^{d})$ is the smallest field of characteristic p that contains the n th primitive roots of unity.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] When computing Brauer characters, one uses the map $\alpha ^{k}\mapsto \exp(2\pi ik/(q-1))$ to map eigenvalues of a representation matrix to the complex numbers.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Under this mapping, the base subfield $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ consists of evenly spaced points around the unit circle (omitting zero).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The order of this field being 26, and the divisors of 6 being 1, 2, 3, 6, the subfields of GF(64) are GF(2), GF(22) = GF(4), GF(23) = GF(8), and GF(64) itself.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As 2 and 3 are coprime, the intersection of GF(4) and GF(8) in GF(64) is the prime field GF(2).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The union of GF(4) and GF(8) has thus 10 elements.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The remaining 54 elements of GF(64) generate GF(64) in the sense that no other subfield contains any of them.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It follows that they are roots of irreducible polynomials of degree 6 over GF(2).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This implies that, over GF(2), there are exactly 9 = ⁠54/6⁠ irreducible monic polynomials of degree 6.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This may be verified by factoring *X*64 − *X* over GF(2).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The elements of GF(64) are primitive *n*th roots of unity for some *n* dividing 63.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As the 3rd and the 7th roots of unity belong to GF(4) and GF(8), respectively, the 54 generators are primitive *n*th roots of unity for some *n* in {9, 21, 63}.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Euler's totient function shows that there are 6 primitive 9th roots of unity, 12 primitive 21st roots of unity, and 36 primitive 63rd roots of unity.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Summing these numbers, one finds again 54 elements.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This shows that the best choice to construct $\mathrm {GF} (64)$ is to define it as GF(2)[*X*] / (*X*6 + *X* + 1).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In fact, this generator is a primitive element, and this polynomial is the irreducible polynomial that produces the easiest Euclidean division.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In this section, p is a prime number, and $q=p^{n}$ is a power of p .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ , the identity (*x* + *y*)*p* = *xp* + *yp* implies that the map $\varphi :x\mapsto x^{p}$ is a $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ -linear endomorphism and a field automorphism of $\mathrm {GF} (q)$ , which fixes every element of the subfield $\mathrm {GF} (p)$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It is called the Frobenius automorphism, after Ferdinand Georg Frobenius.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Denoting by *φk* the composition of *φ* with itself *k* times, we have $\varphi ^{k}:x\mapsto x^{p^{k}}.$ It has been shown in the preceding section that *φ**n* is the identity.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For 0 < *k* < *n*, the automorphism *φ**k* is not the identity, as, otherwise, the polynomial $X^{p^{k}}-X$ would have more than *pk* roots.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] There are no other GF(*p*)-automorphisms of GF(*q*).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In terms of Galois theory, this means that GF(*p**n*) is a Galois extension of GF(*p*), which has a cyclic Galois group.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The fact that the Frobenius map is surjective implies that every finite field is perfect.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] If *F* is a finite field, a non-constant monic polynomial with coefficients in *F* is irreducible over *F*, if it is not the product of two non-constant monic polynomials, with coefficients in *F*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As every polynomial ring over a field is a unique factorization domain, every monic polynomial over a finite field may be factored in a unique way (up to the order of the factors) into a product of irreducible monic polynomials.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] There are efficient algorithms for testing polynomial irreducibility and factoring polynomials over finite fields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] They are a key step for factoring polynomials over the integers or the rational numbers.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] At least for this reason, every computer algebra system has functions for factoring polynomials over finite fields, or, at least, over finite prime fields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The polynomial $X^{q}-X$ factors into linear factors over a field of order *q*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] More precisely, this polynomial is the product of all monic polynomials of degree one over a field of order *q*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This implies that, if *q* = *pn* then *Xq* − *X* is the product of all monic irreducible polynomials over GF(*p*), whose degree divides *n*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In fact, if *P* is an irreducible factor over GF(*p*) of *Xq* − *X*, its degree divides *n*, as its splitting field is contained in GF(*p**n*).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Conversely, if *P* is an irreducible monic polynomial over GF(*p*) of degree *d* dividing *n*, it defines a field extension of degree *d*, which is contained in GF(*p**n*), and all roots of *P* belong to GF(*p**n*), and are roots of *Xq* − *X*; thus *P* divides *Xq* − *X*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] As *Xq* − *X* does not have any multiple factor, it is thus the product of all the irreducible monic polynomials that divide it.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This property is used to compute the product of the irreducible factors of each degree of polynomials over GF(*p*); see *Distinct degree factorization*.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The number *N*(*q*, *n*) of monic irreducible polynomials of degree *n* over GF(*q*) is given by $N(q,n)={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{d\mid n}\mu (d)q^{n/d},$ where *μ* is the Möbius function.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] This formula is an immediate consequence of the property of *X**q* − *X* above and the Möbius inversion formula.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] By the above formula, the number of irreducible (not necessarily monic) polynomials of degree *n* over GF(*q*) is (*q* − 1)*N*(*q*, *n*).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The exact formula implies the inequality $N(q,n)\geq {\frac {1}{n}}{\biggl (}q^{n}-\sum _{\ell \mid n,\ \ell {\text{ prime}}}q^{n/\ell }{\biggr )};$ this is sharp if and only if *n* is a power of some prime.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For every *q* and every *n*, the right hand side is positive, so there is at least one irreducible polynomial of degree *n* over GF(*q*).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] A finite field F is not algebraically closed: the polynomial $f(T)=1+\prod _{\alpha \in F}(T-\alpha ),$ has no roots in F , since *f* (*α*) = 1 for all $\alpha$ in F .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Given a prime number p, let ${\overline {\mathbb {F} }}_{p}$ be an algebraic closure of $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] It is unique up to isomorphism, as holds for an algebraic closure of any given field.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Conway polynomials can be used to construct an explicit algebraic closure of $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For $n\geq 1$ , let $\mathbb {F} _{p^{n}}$ be the set of roots of $x^{p^{n}}-x$ in ${\overline {\mathbb {F} }}_{p}$ ; it is the unique degree n extension of $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ contained in ${\overline {\mathbb {F} }}_{p}$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Any finite field of characteristic p is isomorphic to $\mathbb {F} _{p^{n}}$ for some $n\geq 1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] An algebraic closure of a field serves also as an algebraic closure of any finite subextension, so ${\overline {\mathbb {F} }}_{p}$ is also an algebraic closure of $\mathbb {F} _{p^{n}}$ for each $n\geq 1$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The extension $\mathbb {F} _{p^{n}}/\mathbb {F} _{p}$ is normal (even Galois, even cyclic), so it is preserved by any element of the Galois group $\operatorname {Gal} ({\overline {\mathbb {F} }}_{p}/\mathbb {F} _{p})$ .
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In cryptography, the difficulty of the discrete logarithm problem in a finite field or in an elliptic curve over a finite field is the basis of several widely used protocols, such as the Diffie–Hellman protocol.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For example, in 2014, a secure internet connection to Wikipedia involved the elliptic curve Diffie–Hellman protocol (ECDHE) over a large finite field.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In coding theory, many codes are constructed as subspaces of vector spaces over finite fields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Finite fields are used by many error correction codes, such as Reed–Solomon error correction code or BCH code.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The finite field almost always has characteristic of 2, since computer data is stored in binary.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For example, a byte of data can be interpreted as an element of GF(28).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] One exception is PDF417 bar code, which is GF(929).
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Some CPUs have special instructions that can be useful for finite fields of characteristic 2, generally variations of carry-less product.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Finite fields are widely used in number theory, as many problems over the integers may be solved by reducing them modulo one or several prime numbers.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] For example, the fastest known algorithms for polynomial factorization and linear algebra over the field of rational numbers proceed by reduction modulo one or several primes, and then reconstruction of the solution by using Chinese remainder theorem, Hensel lifting or the LLL algorithm.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Similarly many theoretical problems in number theory can be solved by considering their reductions modulo some or all prime numbers.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Many recent developments of algebraic geometry were motivated by the need to enlarge the power of these modular methods.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Wiles' proof of Fermat's Last Theorem is an example of a deep result involving many mathematical tools, including finite fields.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] The Weil conjectures concern the number of points on algebraic varieties over finite fields and the theory has many applications including exponential and character sum estimates.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] Finite fields have widespread application in combinatorics, two well known examples being the definition of Paley Graphs and the related construction for Hadamard Matrices.
[src:field-theory/finite-field] In arithmetic combinatorics finite fields and finite field models are used extensively, such as in Szemerédi's theorem on arithmetic progressions.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] In abstract algebra, a **splitting field** of a polynomial with coefficients in a field is the smallest field extension of that field over which the polynomial *splits*, i.e., decomposes into linear factors.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] For example, the polynomial $x^{2}-2$ does not factor over the rationals; its splitting field is the smallest extension of the rationals containing ${\sqrt {2}}$ and $-{\sqrt {2}}$ .
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] where $c\in K$ and for each i we have $X-a_{i}\in L[X]$ with *ai* not necessarily distinct and such that the roots *ai* generate *L* over *K*.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The extension *L* is then an extension of minimal degree over *K* in which *p* splits.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] It can be shown that such splitting fields exist and are unique up to isomorphism.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The amount of freedom in that isomorphism is known as the Galois group of *p* (if we assume it is separable).
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] A splitting field of a set *P* of polynomials is the smallest field over which each of the polynomials in *P* splits.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] An extension *L* that is a splitting field for a set of polynomials *p*(*X*) over *K* is called a normal extension of *K*.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Given an algebraically closed field *A* containing *K*, there is a unique splitting field *L* of *p* between *K* and *A*, generated by the roots of *p*.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] If *K* is a subfield of the complex numbers, the existence is immediate.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] On the other hand, the existence of algebraic closures in general is often proved by 'passing to the limit' from the splitting field result, which therefore requires an independent proof to avoid circular reasoning.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Given a separable extension *K*′ of *K*, a **Galois closure** *L* of *K*′ is a type of splitting field, and also a Galois extension of *K* containing *K*′ that is minimal, in an obvious sense.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Such a Galois closure should contain a splitting field for all the polynomials *p* over *K* that are minimal polynomials over *K* of elements of *K*′.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Let *F* be a field and *p*(*X*) be a polynomial in the polynomial ring *F*[*X*] of degree *n*.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The general process for constructing *K*, the splitting field of *p*(*X*) over *F*, is to construct a chain of fields $F=K_{0}\subseteq K_{1}\subseteq \cdots \subseteq K_{r-1}\subseteq K_{r}=K$ such that *Ki* is an extension of *K**i*−1 containing a new root of *p*(*X*).
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Since *p*(*X*) has at most *n* roots the construction will require at most *n* extensions.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The irreducible factor *f*(*X*) used in the quotient construction may be chosen arbitrarily.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Although different choices of factors may lead to different subfield sequences, the resulting splitting fields will be isomorphic.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Since *f*(*X*) is irreducible, (*f*(*X*)) is a maximal ideal of *K**i*[*X*] and *K**i*[*X*] / (*f*(*X*)) is, in fact, a field, the residue field for that maximal ideal.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The degree of a single extension $[K_{i+1}:K_{i}]$ is equal to the degree of the irreducible factor *f*(*X*).
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The elements of *K**i*+1 can be considered as polynomials in *α* of degree less than *n*.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Addition in *K**i*+1 is given by the rules for polynomial addition, and multiplication is given by polynomial multiplication modulo *f*(*X*).
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The remainder *r*(*X*) can be computed through polynomial long division; however there is also a straightforward reduction rule that can be used to compute *r*(*α*) = *g*(*α*)*h*(*α*) directly.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The polynomial is over a field so one can take *f*(*X*) to be monic without loss of generality.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] As an example of the reduction rule, take *Ki* = **Q**[*X*], the ring of polynomials with rational coefficients, and take *f*(*X*) = *X* 7 − 2.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Consider the polynomial ring **R**[*x*], and the irreducible polynomial *x*2 + 1.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] As a result, the elements (or equivalence classes) of **R**[*x*] / (*x*2 + 1) are of the form *a* + *bx* where *a* and *b* belong to **R**.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The addition and multiplication operations are given by firstly using ordinary polynomial addition and multiplication, but then reducing modulo *x*2 + 1, i.e. using the fact that *x*2 ≡ −1, *x*3 ≡ −*x*, *x*4 ≡ 1, *x*5 ≡ *x*, etc.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] We claim that, as a field, the quotient ring **R**[*x*] / (*x*2 + 1) is isomorphic to the complex numbers, **C**.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] A general complex number is of the form *a* + *bi*, where *a* and *b* are real numbers and *i*2 = −1.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] The previous calculations show that addition and multiplication behave the same way in **R**[*x*] / (*x*2 + 1) and **C**.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] In fact, we see that the map between **R**[*x*] / (*x*2 + 1) and **C** given by *a* + *bx* → *a* + *bi* is a homomorphism with respect to addition *and* multiplication.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] It is also obvious that the map *a* + *bx* → *a* + *bi* is both injective and surjective; meaning that *a* + *bx* → *a* + *bi* is a bijective homomorphism, i.e., an isomorphism.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] In 1847, Cauchy used this approach to *define* the complex numbers.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Let K be the rational number field **Q** and *p*(*x*) = *x*3 − 2.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Each root of p equals ${\sqrt[{3}]{2}}$ times a cube root of unity.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] any field containing two distinct roots of p will contain the quotient between two distinct cube roots of unity.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Such a quotient is a primitive cube root of unity—either $\omega _{2}$ or $\omega _{3}=1/\omega _{2}$ .
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] It follows that a splitting field L of p will contain *ω*2, as well as the real cube root of 2; conversely, any extension of **Q** containing these elements contains all the roots of p.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Note that applying the construction process outlined in the previous section to this example, one begins with $K_{0}=\mathbf {Q}$ and constructs the field $K_{1}=\mathbf {Q} [X]/(X^{3}-2)$ .
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] This field is not the splitting field, but contains one (any) root.
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Note that X is not an indeterminate, and is in fact an element of $K_{1}$ .
[src:field-theory/splitting-field] Notice that if we compare this with L from above we can identify $X={\sqrt[{3}]{2}}$ and $Y=\omega _{2}$ .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In mathematics, a **vector space** (also called a **linear space**) is a set whose elements, often called ***vectors***, can be added together and multiplied ("scaled") by numbers called *scalars*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication must satisfy certain requirements, called *vector axioms*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] **Real vector spaces** and **complex vector spaces** are kinds of vector spaces based on different kinds of scalars: real numbers and complex numbers.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Scalars can also be, more generally, elements of any field.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Vector spaces generalize Euclidean vectors, which allow modeling of physical quantities (such as forces and velocity) that have not only a magnitude, but also a direction.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The concept of vector spaces is fundamental for linear algebra, together with the concept of matrices, which allows computing in vector spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This provides a concise and synthetic way for manipulating and studying systems of linear equations.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Vector spaces are characterized by their dimension, which, roughly speaking, specifies the number of independent directions in the space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This means that for two vector spaces over a given field and with the same dimension, the properties that depend only on the vector-space structure are exactly the same (that is, the vector spaces are isomorphic).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A vector space is *finite-dimensional* if its dimension is a natural number.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Otherwise, it is *infinite-dimensional*, and its dimension is an infinite cardinal.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Finite-dimensional vector spaces occur naturally in geometry and related areas.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Infinite-dimensional vector spaces occur in many areas of mathematics.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] For example, polynomial rings are countably infinite-dimensional vector spaces, and many function spaces have the cardinality of the continuum as a dimension.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Many vector spaces that are considered in mathematics are also endowed with other structures.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This is the case of algebras, which include field extensions, polynomial rings, associative algebras and Lie algebras.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This is also the case of topological vector spaces, which include function spaces, inner product spaces, normed spaces, Hilbert spaces and Banach spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In this article, vectors are represented in boldface to distinguish them from scalars.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A vector space over a field F is a non-empty set V together with a binary operation and a binary function that satisfy the eight axioms listed below.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In this context, the elements of V are commonly called *vectors*, and the elements of F are called *scalars*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] To have a vector space, the eight following axioms must be satisfied for every **u**, **v** and **w** in V, and a and b in F.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] When the scalar field is the real numbers, the vector space is called a *real vector space*, and when the scalar field is the complex numbers, the vector space is called a *complex vector space*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] These two cases are the most common ones, but vector spaces with scalars in an arbitrary field F are also commonly considered.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Such a vector space is called an F-*vector space* or a *vector space over F*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Specifically, the distributivity of scalar multiplication with respect to vector addition means that multiplication by a scalar *a* is an endomorphism of the group.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The remaining three axioms establish that the function that maps a scalar *a* to the multiplication by *a* is a ring homomorphism from the field to the endomorphism ring of the group.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Even more concisely, a vector space is a module over a field.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] if and only if they have the same coefficients.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Also equivalently, they are linearly independent if a linear combination results in the zero vector if and only if all its coefficients are zero.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A linear subspace is a vector space for the induced addition and scalar multiplication; this means that the closure property implies that the axioms of a vector space are satisfied.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] of linear subspaces is a linear subspace.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] if its elements are linearly independent and span the vector space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This is a fundamental property of vector spaces, which is detailed in the remainder of the section.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Consider a basis $(\mathbf {b} _{1},\mathbf {b} _{2},\ldots ,\mathbf {b} _{n})$ of a vector space V of dimension n over a field F.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The definition of a basis implies that every $\mathbf {v} \in V$ may be written $\mathbf {v} =a_{1}\mathbf {b} _{1}+\cdots +a_{n}\mathbf {b} _{n},$ with $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ in F, and that this decomposition is unique.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The scalars $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}$ are called the *coordinates* of **v** on the basis.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] They are also said to be the *coefficients* of the decomposition of **v** on the basis.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] One also says that the n-tuple of the coordinates is the coordinate vector of **v** on the basis, since the set $F^{n}$ of the n-tuples of elements of F is a vector space for componentwise addition and scalar multiplication, whose dimension is n.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The one-to-one correspondence between vectors and their coordinate vectors maps vector addition to vector addition and scalar multiplication to scalar multiplication.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] It is thus a vector space isomorphism, which allows translating reasonings and computations on vectors into reasonings and computations on their coordinates.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Vector spaces stem from affine geometry, via the introduction of coordinates in the plane or three-dimensional space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Around 1636, French mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat founded analytic geometry by identifying solutions to an equation of two variables with points on a plane curve.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] To achieve geometric solutions without using coordinates, Bolzano introduced, in 1804, certain operations on points, lines, and planes, which are predecessors of vectors.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Möbius (1827) introduced the notion of barycentric coordinates.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Bellavitis (1833) introduced an equivalence relation on directed line segments that share the same length and direction which he called equipollence.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A Euclidean vector is then an equivalence class of that relation.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Vectors were reconsidered with the presentation of complex numbers by Argand and Hamilton and the inception of quaternions by the latter.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] They are elements in **R**2 and **R**4; treating them using linear combinations goes back to Laguerre in 1867, who also defined systems of linear equations.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In 1857, Cayley introduced the matrix notation which allows for harmonization and simplification of linear maps.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Around the same time, Grassmann studied the barycentric calculus initiated by Möbius.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] He envisaged sets of abstract objects endowed with operations.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In his work, the concepts of linear independence and dimension, as well as scalar products are present.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Grassmann's 1844 work exceeds the framework of vector spaces as well since his considering multiplication led him to what are today called algebras.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Italian mathematician Peano was the first to give the modern definition of vector spaces and linear maps in 1888, although he called them "linear systems".
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Peano's axiomatization allowed for vector spaces with infinite dimension, but Peano did not develop that theory further.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In 1897, Salvatore Pincherle adopted Peano's axioms and made initial inroads into the theory of infinite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] An important development of vector spaces is due to the construction of function spaces by Henri Lebesgue.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This was later formalized by Banach and Hilbert, around 1920.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] At that time, algebra and the new field of functional analysis began to interact, notably with key concepts such as spaces of *p*-integrable functions and Hilbert spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The first example of a vector space consists of arrows in a fixed plane, starting at one fixed point.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This is used in physics to describe forces or velocities.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Given any two such arrows, **v** and **w**, the parallelogram spanned by these two arrows contains one diagonal arrow that starts at the origin, too.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This new arrow is called the *sum* of the two arrows, and is denoted **v** + **w**.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In the special case of two arrows on the same line, their sum is the arrow on this line whose length is the sum or the difference of the lengths, depending on whether the arrows have the same direction.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Another operation that can be done with arrows is scaling: given any positive real number *a*, the arrow that has the same direction as **v**, but is dilated or shrunk by multiplying its length by *a*, is called *multiplication* of **v** by *a*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] When *a* is negative, *a***v** is defined as the arrow pointing in the opposite direction instead.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The following shows a few examples: if *a* = 2, the resulting vector *a***w** has the same direction as **w**, but is stretched to the double length of **w** (the second image).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Moreover, (−1)**v** = −**v** has the opposite direction and the same length as **v** (blue vector pointing down in the second image).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A second key example of a vector space is provided by pairs of real numbers x and y.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The order of the components x and y is significant, so such a pair is also called an ordered pair.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The first example above reduces to this example if an arrow is represented by a pair of Cartesian coordinates of its endpoint.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The simplest example of a vector space over a field *F* is the field *F* itself with its addition viewed as vector addition and its multiplication viewed as scalar multiplication.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] More generally, all *n*-tuples (sequences of length *n*) $(a_{1},a_{2},\dots ,a_{n})$ of elements *a**i* of *F* form a vector space that is usually denoted *F**n* and called a **coordinate space**.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The case *n* = 1 is the above-mentioned simplest example, in which the field *F* is also regarded as a vector space over itself.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The case *F* = **R** and *n* = 2 (so **R**2) reduces to the previous example.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The various axioms of a vector space follow from the fact that the same rules hold for complex number arithmetic.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] More generally, field extensions provide another class of examples of vector spaces, particularly in algebra and algebraic number theory: a field *F* containing a smaller field *E* is an *E*-vector space, by the given multiplication and addition operations of *F*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] For example, the complex numbers are a vector space over **R**, and the field extension $\mathbf {Q} (i{\sqrt {5}})$ is a vector space over **Q**.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Functions from any fixed set Ω to a field *F* also form vector spaces, by performing addition and scalar multiplication pointwise.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] That is, the sum of two functions *f* and *g* is the function $(f+g)$ given by $(f+g)(w)=f(w)+g(w),$ and similarly for multiplication.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Such function spaces occur in many geometric situations, when Ω is the real line or an interval, or other subsets of **R**.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Many notions in topology and analysis, such as continuity, integrability or differentiability are well-behaved with respect to linearity: sums and scalar multiples of functions possessing such a property still have that property.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Therefore, the set of such functions are vector spaces, whose study belongs to functional analysis.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Systems of homogeneous linear equations are closely tied to vector spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] where $A={\begin{bmatrix}1&3&1\\4&2&2\end{bmatrix}}$ is the matrix containing the coefficients of the given equations, $\mathbf {x}$ is the vector $(a,b,c),$ $A\mathbf {x}$ denotes the matrix product, and $\mathbf {0} =(0,0)$ is the zero vector.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In a similar vein, the solutions of homogeneous *linear differential equations* form vector spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] yields $f(x)=ae^{-x}+bxe^{-x},$ where a and b are arbitrary constants, and $e^{x}$ is the natural exponential function.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The relation of two vector spaces can be expressed by *linear map* or *linear transformation*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] An *isomorphism* is a linear map *f* : *V* → *W* such that there exists an inverse map *g* : *W* → *V*, which is a map such that the two possible compositions *f* ∘ *g* : *W* → *W* and *g* ∘ *f* : *V* → *V* are identity maps.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Equivalently, *f* is both one-to-one (injective) and onto (surjective).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] If there exists an isomorphism between *V* and *W*, the two spaces are said to be *isomorphic*; they are then essentially identical as vector spaces, since all identities holding in *V* are, via *f*, transported to similar ones in *W*, and vice versa via *g*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Conversely, given a pair (*x*, *y*), the arrow going by *x* to the right (or to the left, if *x* is negative), and *y* up (down, if *y* is negative) turns back the arrow **v**.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Linear maps *V* → *W* between two vector spaces form a vector space Hom*F*(*V*, *W*), also denoted L(*V*, *W*), or 𝓛(*V*, *W*).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The space of linear maps from *V* to *F* is called the *dual vector space*, denoted *V*∗.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Via the injective natural map *V* → *V*∗∗, any vector space can be embedded into its *bidual*; the map is an isomorphism if and only if the space is finite-dimensional.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Once a basis of *V* is chosen, linear maps *f* : *V* → *W* are completely determined by specifying the images of the basis vectors, because any element of *V* is expressed uniquely as a linear combination of them.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] If dim *V* = dim *W*, a 1-to-1 correspondence between fixed bases of *V* and *W* gives rise to a linear map that maps any basis element of *V* to the corresponding basis element of *W*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] It is an isomorphism, by its very definition.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Therefore, two vector spaces over a given field are isomorphic if their dimensions agree and vice versa.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Another way to express this is that any vector space over a given field is *completely classified* (up to isomorphism) by its dimension, a single number.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In particular, any *n*-dimensional *F*-vector space *V* is isomorphic to *F**n*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] However, there is no "canonical" or preferred isomorphism; an isomorphism *φ* : *F**n* → *V* is equivalent to the choice of a basis of *V*, by mapping the standard basis of *F**n* to *V*, via *φ*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Moreover, after choosing bases of *V* and *W*, *any* linear map *f* : *V* → *W* is uniquely represented by a matrix via this assignment.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The determinant det (*A*) of a square matrix *A* is a scalar that tells whether the associated map is an isomorphism or not: to be so it is sufficient and necessary that the determinant is nonzero.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The linear transformation of **R***n* corresponding to a real *n*-by-*n* matrix is orientation preserving if and only if its determinant is positive.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Endomorphisms, linear maps *f* : *V* → *V*, are particularly important since in this case vectors **v** can be compared with their image under *f*, *f*(**v**).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Any nonzero vector **v** satisfying *λ***v** = *f*(**v**), where *λ* is a scalar, is called an *eigenvector* of *f* with *eigenvalue* *λ*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Equivalently, **v** is an element of the kernel of the difference *f* − *λ* · Id (where Id is the identity map *V* → *V*).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] If the field *F* is large enough to contain a zero of this polynomial (which automatically happens for *F* algebraically closed, such as *F* = **C**) any linear map has at least one eigenvector.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The vector space *V* may or may not possess an eigenbasis, a basis consisting of eigenvectors.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This phenomenon is governed by the Jordan canonical form of the map.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The set of all eigenvectors corresponding to a particular eigenvalue of *f* forms a vector space known as the *eigenspace* corresponding to the eigenvalue (and *f*) in question.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In addition to the above concrete examples, there are a number of standard linear algebraic constructions that yield vector spaces related to given ones.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A nonempty subset W of a vector space V that is closed under addition and scalar multiplication (and therefore contains the $\mathbf {0}$ -vector of V ) is called a *linear subspace* of V , or simply a *subspace* of V , when the ambient space is unambiguously a vector space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Subspaces of V are vector spaces (over the same field) in their own right.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The intersection of all subspaces containing a given set S of vectors is called its span, and it is the smallest subspace of V containing the set S .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Expressed in terms of elements, the span is the subspace consisting of all the linear combinations of elements of S .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Linear subspace of dimension 1 and 2 are referred to as a *line* (also *vector line*), and a *plane* respectively.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] If *W* is an *n*-dimensional vector space, any subspace of dimension 1 less, i.e., of dimension $n-1$ is called a *hyperplane*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The counterpart to subspaces are *quotient vector spaces*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Given any subspace $W\subseteq V$ , the quotient space $V/W$ (" V modulo W ") is defined as follows: as a set, it consists of $\mathbf {v} +W=\{\mathbf {v} +\mathbf {w} :\mathbf {w} \in W\},$ where $\mathbf {v}$ is an arbitrary vector in V .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The sum of two such elements $\mathbf {v} _{1}+W$ and $\mathbf {v} _{2}+W$ is $\left(\mathbf {v} _{1}+\mathbf {v} _{2}\right)+W$ , and scalar multiplication is given by $a\cdot (\mathbf {v} +W)=(a\cdot \mathbf {v} )+W$ .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The key point in this definition is that $\mathbf {v} _{1}+W=\mathbf {v} _{2}+W$ if and only if the difference of $\mathbf {v} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {v} _{2}$ lies in W .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] This way, the quotient space "forgets" information that is contained in the subspace W .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The kernel $\ker(f)$ of a linear map $f:V\to W$ consists of vectors $\mathbf {v}$ that are mapped to $\mathbf {0}$ in W .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The kernel and the image $\operatorname {im} (f)=\{f(\mathbf {v} ):\mathbf {v} \in V\}$ are subspaces of V and W , respectively.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] An important example is the kernel of a linear map $\mathbf {x} \mapsto A\mathbf {x}$ for some fixed matrix A .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The kernel of this map is the subspace of vectors $\mathbf {x}$ such that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {0}$ , which is precisely the set of solutions to the system of homogeneous linear equations belonging to A .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In the corresponding map $f\mapsto D(f)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}a_{i}{\frac {d^{i}f}{dx^{i}}},$ the derivatives of the function f appear linearly (as opposed to $f^{\prime \prime }(x)^{2}$ , for example).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Since differentiation is a linear procedure (that is, $(f+g)^{\prime }=f^{\prime }+g^{\prime }$ and $(c\cdot f)^{\prime }=c\cdot f^{\prime }$ for a constant c ) this assignment is linear, called a linear differential operator.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] In particular, the solutions to the differential equation $D(f)=0$ form a vector space (over **R** or **C**).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The existence of kernels and images is part of the statement that the category of vector spaces (over a fixed field F ) is an abelian category, that is, a corpus of mathematical objects and structure-preserving maps between them (a category) that behaves much like the category of abelian groups.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The *direct product* of vector spaces and the *direct sum* of vector spaces are two ways of combining an indexed family of vector spaces into a new vector space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The *direct product* $\textstyle {\prod _{i\in I}V_{i}}$ of a family of vector spaces $V_{i}$ consists of the set of all tuples $\left(\mathbf {v} _{i}\right)_{i\in I}$ , which specify for each index i in some index set I an element $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ of $V_{i}$ .
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] Addition and scalar multiplication is performed componentwise.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] A variant of this construction is the *direct sum* ${\textstyle \bigoplus _{i\in I}V_{i}}$ (also called coproduct and denoted ${\textstyle \coprod _{i\in I}V_{i}}$ ), where only tuples with finitely many nonzero vectors are allowed.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] If the index set I is finite, the two constructions agree, but in general they are different.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The *tensor product* $V\otimes _{F}W,$ or simply $V\otimes W,$ of two vector spaces V and W is one of the central notions of multilinear algebra, which deals with extending notions such as linear maps to several variables.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p01] The tensor product is a particular vector space that is a *universal* recipient of bilinear maps $g,$ as follows.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] From the point of view of linear algebra, vector spaces are completely understood insofar as any vector space over a given field is characterized, up to isomorphism, by its dimension.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] However, vector spaces *per se* do not offer a framework to deal with the question—crucial to analysis—whether a sequence of functions converges to another function.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Likewise, linear algebra is not adapted to deal with infinite series, since the addition operation allows only finitely many terms to be added.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Therefore, the needs of functional analysis require considering additional structures.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] A vector space may be given a partial order $\,\leq ,\,$ under which some vectors can be compared.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, n -dimensional real space $\mathbf {R} ^{n}$ can be ordered by comparing its vectors componentwise.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Ordered vector spaces, for example Riesz spaces, are fundamental to Lebesgue integration, which relies on the ability to express a function as a difference of two positive functions $f=f^{+}-f^{-}.$ where $f^{+}$ denotes the positive part of f and $f^{-}$ the negative part.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] "Measuring" vectors is done by specifying a norm, a datum which measures lengths of vectors, or by an inner product, which measures angles between vectors.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Norms and inner products are denoted $|\mathbf {v} |$ and $\langle \mathbf {v} ,\mathbf {w} \rangle ,$ respectively.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Convergence questions are treated by considering vector spaces V carrying a compatible topology, a structure that allows one to talk about elements being close to each other.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Compatible here means that addition and scalar multiplication have to be continuous maps.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In such *topological vector spaces* one can consider series of vectors.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The mode of convergence of the series depends on the topology imposed on the function space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In such cases, pointwise convergence and uniform convergence are two prominent examples.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] A way to ensure the existence of limits of certain infinite series is to restrict attention to spaces where any Cauchy sequence has a limit; such a vector space is called complete.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Roughly, a vector space is complete provided that it contains all necessary limits.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, the vector space of polynomials on the unit interval $[0,1],$ equipped with the topology of uniform convergence is not complete because any continuous function on $[0,1]$ can be uniformly approximated by a sequence of polynomials, by the Weierstrass approximation theorem.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In contrast, the space of *all* continuous functions on $[0,1]$ with the same topology is complete.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Their study—a key piece of functional analysis—focuses on infinite-dimensional vector spaces, since all norms on finite-dimensional topological vector spaces give rise to the same notion of convergence.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The image at the right shows the equivalence of the 1 -norm and $\infty$ -norm on $\mathbf {R} ^{2}:$ as the unit "balls" enclose each other, a sequence converges to zero in one norm if and only if it so does in the other norm.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In the infinite-dimensional case, however, there will generally be inequivalent topologies, which makes the study of topological vector spaces richer than that of vector spaces without additional data.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] From a conceptual point of view, all notions related to topological vector spaces should match the topology.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, instead of considering all linear maps (also called functionals) $V\to W,$ maps between topological vector spaces are required to be continuous.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In particular, the (topological) dual space $V^{*}$ consists of continuous functionals $V\to \mathbf {R}$ (or to $\mathbf {C}$ ).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The fundamental Hahn–Banach theorem is concerned with separating subspaces of appropriate topological vector spaces by continuous functionals.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Imposing boundedness conditions not only on the function, but also on its derivatives leads to Sobolev spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Complete inner product spaces are known as *Hilbert spaces*, in honor of David Hilbert.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The Hilbert space $L^{2}(\Omega ),$ with inner product given by $\langle f\ ,\ g\rangle =\int _{\Omega }f(x){\overline {g(x)}}\,dx,$ where ${\overline {g(x)}}$ denotes the complex conjugate of $g(x),$ is a key case.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] By definition, in a Hilbert space, any Cauchy sequence converges to a limit.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Conversely, finding a sequence of functions $f_{n}$ with desirable properties that approximate a given limit function is equally crucial.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Early analysis, in the guise of the Taylor approximation, established an approximation of differentiable functions f by polynomials.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] By the Stone–Weierstrass theorem, every continuous function on $[a,b]$ can be approximated as closely as desired by a polynomial.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] A similar approximation technique by trigonometric functions is commonly called Fourier expansion, and is much applied in engineering.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Such a set of functions is called a *basis* of $H,$ its cardinality is known as the Hilbert space dimension.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Not only does the theorem exhibit suitable basis functions as sufficient for approximation purposes, but also together with the Gram–Schmidt process, it enables one to construct a basis of orthogonal vectors.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Such orthogonal bases are the Hilbert space generalization of the coordinate axes in finite-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The solutions to various differential equations can be interpreted in terms of Hilbert spaces.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, a great many fields in physics and engineering lead to such equations, and frequently solutions with particular physical properties are used as basis functions, often orthogonal.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] As an example from physics, the time-dependent Schrödinger equation in quantum mechanics describes the change of physical properties in time by means of a partial differential equation, whose solutions are called wavefunctions.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Definite values for physical properties such as energy, or momentum, correspond to eigenvalues of a certain (linear) differential operator and the associated wavefunctions are called eigenstates.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The spectral theorem decomposes a linear compact operator acting on functions in terms of these eigenfunctions and their eigenvalues.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] General vector spaces do not possess a multiplication between vectors.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] A vector space equipped with an additional bilinear operator defining the multiplication of two vectors is an *algebra over a field* (or *F*-algebra if the field *F* is specified).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, the set of all polynomials $p(t)$ forms an algebra known as the polynomial ring: using that the sum of two polynomials is a polynomial, they form a vector space; they form an algebra since the product of two polynomials is again a polynomial.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Rings of polynomials (in several variables) and their quotients form the basis of algebraic geometry, because they are rings of functions of algebraic geometric objects.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Examples include the vector space of n -by- n matrices, with $[x,y]=xy-yx,$ the commutator of two matrices, and $\mathbf {R} ^{3},$ endowed with the cross product.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The tensor algebra $\operatorname {T} (V)$ is a formal way of adding products to any vector space V to obtain an algebra.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] As a vector space, it is spanned by symbols, called simple tensors $\mathbf {v} _{1}\otimes \mathbf {v} _{2}\otimes \cdots \otimes \mathbf {v} _{n},$ where the degree n varies.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The multiplication is given by concatenating such symbols, imposing the distributive law under addition, and requiring that scalar multiplication commute with the tensor product ⊗, much the same way as with the tensor product of two vector spaces introduced in the above section on tensor products.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] A *vector bundle* is a family of vector spaces parametrized continuously by a topological space *X*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] More precisely, a vector bundle over *X* is a topological space *E* equipped with a continuous map $\pi :E\to X$ such that for every *x* in *X*, the fiber π−1(*x*) is a vector space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The case dim *V* = 1 is called a line bundle.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For any vector space *V*, the projection *X* × *V* → *X* makes the product *X* × *V* into a "trivial" vector bundle.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Vector bundles over *X* are required to be locally a product of *X* and some (fixed) vector space *V*: for every *x* in *X*, there is a neighborhood *U* of *x* such that the restriction of π to π−1(*U*) is isomorphic to the trivial bundle *U* × *V* → *U*.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Despite their locally trivial character, vector bundles may (depending on the shape of the underlying space *X*) be "twisted" in the large (that is, the bundle need not be (globally isomorphic to) the trivial bundle *X* × *V*).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, the Möbius strip can be seen as a line bundle over the circle *S*1 (by identifying open intervals with the real line).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] It is, however, different from the cylinder *S*1 × **R**, because the latter is orientable whereas the former is not.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Properties of certain vector bundles provide information about the underlying topological space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] For example, the tangent bundle consists of the collection of tangent spaces parametrized by the points of a differentiable manifold.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The tangent bundle of the circle *S*1 is globally isomorphic to *S*1 × **R**, since there is a global nonzero vector field on *S*1.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In contrast, by the hairy ball theorem, there is no (tangent) vector field on the 2-sphere *S*2 which is everywhere nonzero.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] K-theory studies the isomorphism classes of all vector bundles over some topological space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] In addition to deepening topological and geometrical insight, it has purely algebraic consequences, such as the classification of finite-dimensional real division algebras: **R**, **C**, the quaternions **H** and the octonions **O**.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The cotangent bundle of a differentiable manifold consists, at every point of the manifold, of the dual of the tangent space, the cotangent space.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Sections of that bundle are known as differential one-forms.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Roughly, *affine spaces* are vector spaces whose origins are not specified.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] More precisely, an affine space is a set with a free transitive vector space action.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] An important example is the space of solutions of a system of inhomogeneous linear equations $A\mathbf {v} =\mathbf {b}$ generalizing the homogeneous case discussed in the above section on linear equations, which can be found by setting $\mathbf {b} =\mathbf {0}$ in this equation.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The space of solutions is the affine subspace **x** + *V* where **x** is a particular solution of the equation, and *V* is the space of solutions of the homogeneous equation (the nullspace of *A*).
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] The set of one-dimensional subspaces of a fixed finite-dimensional vector space *V* is known as *projective space*; it may be used to formalize the idea of parallel lines intersecting at infinity.
[src:field-theory/vector-space-p02] Grassmannians and flag manifolds generalize this by parametrizing linear subspaces of fixed dimension *k* and flags of subspaces, respectively.
